(
    'Mapungubwe Archive',
    '1220/1250',
    'The <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m025rs2z">gold</a> hemispherical bowl or vessel from <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill (AD 1220- Ad 1290) was excavated in 1934 from the Original Gold Grave (M1 A620). This item forms part of the National Heritage Collection and was reconstructed and restored by the British Museum in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> in 2001. The gold foil is formed using indigenous technology, folded up from a single foil sheet into a bowl shape, unevenly hammered and formed onto a wood core. Partly shaped by repoussï¿½ work, but also pleated near the rim. The edges of the vessel are folded inwards to form a rim. A multitude of small holes in many places around the walls of the bowl, mark the position for nail perforations, evidence of original mounting on a wooded former. Other holes mark places of attachments for decorative appliques; some are surrounded by a circular wear mark or impressions (ï¿½1cm), which indicate the original presence of a stud of decorative feature on the outer surface. The actual function of the this gold vessel remains unknown, but it carries symbolic value as a sacred burial object that was once associated with the elite that lived and were buried on Mapungubwe Hill. Mapungubwe was decl',
