    'de Porceleyne Fles',
    '1939',
    'This World War II (1939-1945) Delft blue and white plate depicts a Dutch ship sailing the rough seas against a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0z71l">storm</a> with dark skies and the ï¿½all seeing eyeï¿½ or God watching over them. The inscription honors the 6th stanza of The Netherlandï¿½s national anthem, ï¿½Mijn schild en de betrouwen zijt gij, O God Mjin Heerï¿½ meaning ï¿½my shield and reliance are you, o God my Lordï¿½. It was created shortly after hostilities in the Second World War (1939-1945) commenced and prays to God to keep <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">the Netherlands</a> safe. The plate is decorated on the back with two circular parallel blue lines and marked <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a> and was sold in Philippona, a fine porcelain tableware and accessories shop in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07g0_">Sï¿½Gravenhage</a>.',
