(
    'Piercy Eagle',
    '1910',
    'The facade of the Old Arts Building with its iconic <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x3z">clock</a> tower, slate floors and sandstone <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03nfmq">architecture</a> is an iconic feature of the University of Pretoria and home to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> Museums. A bronze sculpture of two Red Lechwes designed in 1970 by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> sculptor, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02wvpsn">Coert Steynberg</a> (1905-1982) lies in front of the buildings courtyard.   The Old Arts Building was designed by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a>-born Architect, Piercy James (Patrick) <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09csl">Eagle</a> (1875-1932), a student of the renowned architect, Sir Herbert Baker. Its architecture reflects different styles and elements from Cape-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">Dutch</a> to Neo-Romanesque. The building still features the original stain-glass <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0d4v4">windows</a>, slate floors and Oregon pine flooring. It was declared a South African National Monument and officiate as a museum in 1968.',
