    'Allina Ndebele',
    '2000',
    'Two friends, a woven <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09kxp">woolen</a> tapestry by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Allina Ndebele (b.1939) done in 2000. This work was purchased from the artist when she exhibited at the University of Pretoria in 2000. Short Biography: Allina Ndebele was born in 1939 at the Ekuhlengeni Mission station in the Vryheid District of KwaZulu Natal. After studying her junior certificate and applying for nursing training, Ndebele enrolled in what is today known as the Rorkes Drift Art Centre in 1963. After training as a weaver in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0d0vqn">Sweden</a> on an art scholarship, Ndebele returned to teach at Rorkes Drift and stayed there until 1977. After that she decided to start her solo career as a weaving artist, moving back to her home near the Black Umfolozi River. It took her until 1985 to receive any kind of recognition when she was invited to a solo exhibition of her tapestries at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> Art Museum. In 2005 Ndebele was awarded the Presidential Order of Ikhamanga for her contributions in the field of the creative arts.',
