    '2008',
    'A digital print and enamel on canvas work of 2023 titled, Chris Hani by the South African artist Wayne Barker (b.1973) . Wayne Barker''s irreverent take on <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m043cgm">JH Pierneef</a>''s landscapes, especially his iconic Apies River scene, garnered attention in the 1980s. Barker''s pop-influenced paintings, often featuring commercial brands and rudimentary figures, challenged the traditional art establishment. Despite criticism, Barker persisted, using Pierneef''s work to comment on globalization and South Africa''s evolving identity. His later works, including collaborations with artisans, continued to blur boundaries, considering Pierneef as a pop artist and his pieces as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> "first pop images." In this painting Baker uses the image of Chris Hani, the leader of the South African Communist Party and chief of staff of uMkhonto we Sizwe, the armed wing of the African National Congress who was assassinated in 1993. This artwork was acquired by means of purchase in 2023 for the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> Art Collection.',
