    'WMG ten Hacken',
    '1940',
    'A World War II (1939-1945) earthenware plate made on commission for a stationary dealer P.A.W. Philippona in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07g0_">The Hague</a>,<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a>. The plate depicted with a willow <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">tree</a> and war burial is inscribed, ï¿½getrouw tot in den doodï¿½ meaning ï¿½faithful until death.ï¿½ It is commemorative war plate dedicated to the fallen heroes that fought the Battle of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06hdk">Rotterdam</a> between 10 and 14 May 1940 which ended with the German occupation of the Dutch city. The plate was painted by WMG Ten Hacken for <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04825h">De Porceleyne Fles</a> or the Porcelain Jar factory in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a>. The plate was donated by Louise van Gybland Oosterhoff as the second of a three part donation of items and documents on Dutch history to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1946.',
