(
    'H Visser',
    '1926',
    'An archival <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m068jd">photograph</a> of the Extra-Mural Building in Pretoria in 1926. The MacFadyen Memorial Hall was in the University of Pretoria''s Extra-Mural Building at 239 Vermeulen Street in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. Professor Martin du Toit initiated a series of art exhibitions in the Macfadyen Hall from 1931 to 1938, to display the work of contemporary, often contentious South African and international artists. The university wished to support artists and provided this exhibition space free of charge. As a token of appreciation, many artists donated artwork at the end of the exhibition. Du Toit used these exhibitions as a starting point in building up a representative collection of South African art, which he augmented with donations from artists and art collectors. The MacFadyen Memorial Hall hosted many art exhibitions from 1931 until 1951 in Pretoria. Artists such as Irma Stern, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hrf0cv">Maggie Laubser</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0lqfrk5">Gregoire Boonzaier</a>, Alexis Preller and many of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> most significant artists exhibited at the MacFadyen Memorial Hall and also donated artwork after these exhibitions. These exhibitions lead to the University of Pretoria''s art collection, which was one of the earliest established art collections within South Africa. Public awareness of the notion of modernism began to grow thanks to the exposure of these artists in Pretoria',
