    'P van der Want',
    '1919',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">World War I</a> Dutch Ivora annexation plate created by the P van der Want Plateelbakkerij Ivora or Ivora <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">Ceramic</a> Kiln, in the town of Gouda in 1919 as a commission for C. Fortmann. This plate shows the annexation plans of Zeeland, Limburg, Western Scheldt, North Brabant and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04g61">Luxembourg</a> to form part of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0154j">Belgium</a> after the war. The coat of arms of Zeeland and Limburg are on the rim with a central <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04_tb">map</a>. After the war, Belgium hoped that The Netherlands should be punished for staying neutral during the war and as a result requested the annexation of a large part of The Netherlands as their compensation. This war time plan, however was never approved in the post-war peace treaties.',
