(
    'Max Pechstein',
    '1923',
    'A polychrome lithograph titled Still life with figurine by the German artist Max Pechstein (1881-1955). The work was donated to the University by the artist in 1935 when the University had an exhibition by Modern German artists. Short Biography: <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07qd_6">Hermann Max Pechstein</a> was born in 1881 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f_rk">Zwickau</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>. He studied at the Royal Art Academy in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09b9m">Dresden</a>. He fought on the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dl4z">Western Front</a> during the First <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">World War (1914-1918</a>) and became part of a radical Socialist group after the war. In 1922 he became a professor at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0156q">Berlin</a> Academy and in 1933 he was banned from exhibiting in Germany by the Nazi''s. At this stage he exhibited in other countries which included <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a>. After 1945 he was reinstated as a Professor He died in 1955 in West Berlin.',
