    '1926',
    'An early archival photograph from 1926 of a view of the exterior of the MacFadyen Memorial Hall in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, where the Transvaal University Collection (later become the University of Pretoria) held some of its earliest art exhibitions. Professor Martin Lourens du Toit (1897-1938) served as a patron of South African visual art in the 1930s and the first Head of the Department of Afrikaans. He initiated a series of more than 25 art exhibitions in the MacFadyen Memorial Hall from 1931 to 1939, to display the work of South African artists, often contentious artists. The University of Pretoria supported the artists and provided the exhibition space free of charge at the time. As a token of appreciation, many artists donated their artwork at the end of each exhibition. Du Toit used these exhibitions as a starting point in building up a representative collection of South African art, which he augmented with donations from other artists and art collectors. Several artists such as Irma Stern, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hrf0cv">Maggie Laubser</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0lqfrk5">Gregoire Boonzaier</a>, Alexis Preller and many 20th century, (now iconic) <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> most significant artists exhibited at the MacFadyen Memorial Hall, after which they donated their works to the University of Pretoria. The MacFadyen Memorial Hall continued to host many art exhibitions between 1931 until 1951, and so began laying a foundation of an institutional art collection at the University of Pretoria, which became one of the earliest established art collections within South Africa.',
