    'Claudette Schreuders',
    '2017',
    'A lithograph, titled, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05g7q">Mandela</a> created in 2017 by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Claudette Schreuders (b. 1973). Schreuders work is a reflection of the search for an <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> identity in a post-apartheid South Africa. The narratives in Schreudersï¿½ works explore African and European identities within a post-apartheid South Africa. Her figures, whether it is her sculpture or prints, are loaded with meaning and emotions that reach beyond cultural boundaries. Schreudersï¿½ works furthermore demonstrate hybrid notions of meaning and form, influenced by Blolo and Colon figures of West Africa and the elements of medieval church <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> and Spanish portraiture. Schreuders is mainly known for her painted wooden figures. Short Biography: Claudette Schreuders was born in 1973 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> South Africa. Schreuders graduated with a Masterï¿½s degree from the Michaelis School of Fine Art in 1998. Schreuders currently lives and works in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a>, South Africa. Schreuders has exhibited extensively within South Africa and internationally. In 1999, she was part of the Liberated Voices exhibition at the Museum for African Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02_286">New York</a>. Schreuders had a solo exhibition ï¿½Burnt by the Sunï¿½ at the Jack Shainman Gallery in New York in 2001.',
