    '1929',
    'A 1929 oil painting of the Old Arts Building of the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> is by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist, William George Bevington (1881-1953), depicting a veld-type foreground and the Old Arts Building centrally located with looming rain clouds in the background. The painting depicts a period when the Old Arts Building was enveloped invasively by green ivy. The ivy covering the building was the so-called, ï¿½<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01cx_">Boston</a> Ivyï¿½, native to the East Coast of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09c7w0">United States</a>, hence the source of the phrase an "Ivy-League University". In 1991, the ivy was completely removed from the building by the company Holm, Jordan &amp; Holm due to the large-scale damage it was doing to the historic sandstone. The rain clouds are depicted to create dark shadows from the tree on the left entering the picture plane and draw the shadows towards the beginnings of a garden and small water feature. Parts of the lawn are green with some <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">flowers</a> in bloom suggesting spring. The walls of the building are painted greyish instead of the typical orange-type colour of sandstone. Thus, the Old Arts Building appears heavy, quiet, and empty with bare sand as a courtyard, suggesting no personal or people interacting with the landscape space, there is a portion of a palm <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">tree</a> on the right. Short Biography:  William George Graham Bevington was born in 1881, in Seymour in the Eastern Cape. He studied at the Rhodes University in Grahamstown from 1903. In 1906, he was awarded the Rhodes Bursary to study at the Kensington Royal College of Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a>. Bevington was deaf, mute and held several teaching positions and was the illustrative cartoonist for the newspaper, Cape Times. Not much is known about his later life, he passed away on 4 October 1953 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a>.',
