    'World War I Dutch Ivora armistice plate created by the P van der Want Plateelbakkerij Ivora or Ivora Ceramic Kiln, in the town of Gouda in 1918 as a commission for the stationary dealer M Pollman in the town of Hees in The Netherlands. Pollman was known to commission war wares in order to sell in his stationary shop, often marketing the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramics</a> as ï¿½Bezondere Uitgave Pollmanï¿½ or Pollmanï¿½s Special Edition.  This plate marks the armistice between the Allies and Germany that was signed in a carriage in the forest of Compiï¿½gne in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a> to commence at 11h00 on 11 November 1918. Signatories were <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01w_xd">Ferdinand Foch</a> (France), Matias Erzberger (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>), <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083q7">Woodrow Wilson</a> (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09c7w0">USA</a>) and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cmtr">Lloyd George</a> (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">Great Britain</a>) whose names are inscribed and hailed as heroes for ending <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">the First World War</a>.',
