    'Minotaurus is a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> by the Eswatini (formerly known as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06v36">Swaziland</a>) artist Nandipha Mntambo (b.1982). The minotaur is a mythical creature in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m035qy">Greek</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04zhd">mythology</a> portrayed as half man and half bull, an often fierce and daunting figure. In this artistï¿½s version of the legendary beast, Mntambo inserts herself into the body of the Minotaur, displaying the female body in a warrior stance. Yet with the head tilted downwards and the facial expression submissive with a soft downwards gaze. The ambiguous figure expresses a femininity that is fighting to emerge or symbolise the last moments of the life of the Minotaur, relieved to be delivered from a surreal and lonely experience.',
