    'Louis Olivier',
    '2018',
    'The RMB Think Bench was a collaboration between the artist Louis Olivier and student artists Nkhensani Rihlampfu, Allan Laing and George Halloway, as well as Olivier''s team from Workhorse Bronze Foundry. This 10-ton <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01mxf">concrete</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculptural</a> bench has been installed on the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>ï¿½s Hatfield campus, located between the Merensky Library and the Student Centre. The sculpture becomes an interactive bench that can host more than 20 students seated over the different letters in the word ''think''. For RMB the intention behind the Think Bench was to find a way for young talent to congregate and contribute through having conversations that matter. Being a bench for students, it was imperative that young artists were involved in the creation, hence two assistant artists being mentored throughout the process. Olivier involved a diverse group of student artists, giving them the opportunity to be mentored and to develop their skills. Nkhensani Rihlapfu and Allen Laing are assistant artists and were involved with the conceptual development of the work, while George Halloway joined the team at a later stage to work on the technical side and for the upscaling of the modelled pieces.',
