    'Christo Coetzee',
    '1991',
    'This oil on Board work is titled, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">Flowers</a> by the South African artist Christo Coetzee (1929-2000) created in 1991.Throughout the artists career, flowers such as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06m11">roses</a> were an important subject in Coetzeeï¿½s paintings and roses also played an important role in his life. Rose bushes large and small filled the front and back yard of Coetzeeï¿½s House in Tulbagh in the Cape and was considered his favoured flower. This work shows a full bouquet of large pink roses in a glass <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02s195">vase</a>, a typical Coetzee subject or still-life. Short biography. The Johannesburg born artist, Christo Coetzee pursued his art studies at the Slade School of Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> as a complementary tuition exercise to his fine art degree qualification acquired from the University of the Witwatersrand in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> South Africa. Most of Coetzee''s works are mainly colourful, stylized figurative images and still-life. After completing his studies he moved to Europe on a Government Travelling Scholarship and become part of the Stadler Stable in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> before moving to Finestrat in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06mkj">Spain</a>. Later, Coetzee went to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japan</a> where he was invited to join the Gutai Group, the first radical Art Group in post-war Japan. It was in Japan that Coetzee developed his later art style that ultimately classified him as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> leading and prominent avant-garde artists. Coetzee received international recognition for his contribution to the avant-garde art movements known as Art Informel, Assemblage and Neo-Baroque in Paris, Spain and Japan during the 1950s and 1960s, an art style he perfected. He passed away at the age of 71 in 2000 in Tulbagh in the Cape and bequeathed his entire home and collection to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>.',
