    'Han van Meegeren',
    '1939',
    'A lithograph by the Dutch artist Han van Meegeren titled Storks. The work itself is not of great quality but rather the story behind it. In 1939 when this was done Van Meegeren was an Unattributed artist in the Netherlands by 1947 when he passed away he would be world renowned for creating works he faked of Johannes Vermeer and selling them to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03hy3">Herman Gï¿½ring</a> the Reichsmarschall of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>, the highest rank in the Military during the Nazi regime. Short Biography: Henricus Antonius "Han" van Meegeren (1889-1947) was a dutch artist and one of the most notorious forgers of the 20th Century in Europe. As he was criticized as not being a good artist he forged works by artist like <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0bw2x">Johannes Vermeer</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ch5l">Frans Hals</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02sfvv">Pieter de Hooch</a> and Gerard ter Bosch. His forgeries was so good that certain art experts of his era maintained that they were real. Facing the Death penalty in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a> for traiding cultural property to the Nazi''s he admitted to forgery and even painted a fake in court to prove his innocence.',
