    'Jean Kotze-Louw',
    '1889',
    'A dry-point etching titled, Entry into Jerusalem by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Jean Kotze-Louw (1929-2014). Her work is a modern artist''s depiction of a Byzantine-styled artwork.  Washing of the Feet depicts a man on a donkey, Jesus riding towards a city and surrounded by people. On right is the figure of a man in a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">tree</a>, who climbed the tree for a better view of Jesus. The scene shows Jesus entering Jerusalem shortly before his crucifixion. The man in the tree is Zacchaeus who climbed a Sycamore tree to witness Jesus entering the holy city. The painting depict salvation as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzmg">Zacchaeus</a> was a tax collector and seen by most of his contemporaries as corrupt and a traitor. Short Biography: Jean Kotze-Louw was born in 1929 in Lichtenburg in the North West Province. She studied fine arts from 1947 to 1951 at the University of Natal and after winning the Emma Smith Scholarship in 1950 she continued her studies in Italy, and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>. Between 1958 and 1960 she began her career as an academic as a lecturer in mosaic at the Positano Art Workshop in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italy</a>. In 1975 she became a lecturer of Visual Design and Painting at the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. She published an article on Byzantine mosaic artworks in 1968 and research that became a large part of her later artworks.',
