    'Thero Makepe',
    '2020',
    'A digital photograph on Hahnemï¿½hle paper, titled, Robben Island University by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist ,Thero Makepe (b.1996). The work forms part of a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m068jd">photographic</a> series by the artist, titled: ï¿½We Didn''t Choose to be Born Hereï¿½. The series explores Makepeï¿½s family history, including themes such as exile and activism. Each portrait focuses on an individual, while the landscapes bring to light themes of sacrifice and love. Makepe uses his familyï¿½s personal archives, as well as public archives, to make a study into the lives of different family members during times of separation and crises. Robben Island University places special focus on his familyï¿½s experiences in the prison on the Island. The work depicts the limestone quarry on the island, where inmates gathered and traded knowledge. This transfer of knowledge should be considered against the historical background of the denying and restriction of education for people of colour by the Apartheid government, and therefore makes it a vital tale in the complete history of education in South Africa. The artist further illustrates the value of inter-generational value that stretches beyond the simple relaying of information. This artwork was acquired by means of purchase in 2023 for the University of Pretoria Art Collection.',
