    'Carimbwe Katunga',
    '1995',
    'This work titled, Three buck, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015p6">bird</a> and snake by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0j4b">Angolan</a> born artist Carimbwe Katunga (b.1958). Katunga was part of the Platfontein Art Group, a relocated community of !Xu and Khwe people displaced from Angola during the wars of the 1970s and 1980s. They were resettled at Platfontein near Schmidtsdrift outside <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjpx">Kimberley</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a> and in the 1990s the community were resettled again at Wildebeeskuil. The community consists of two San tribes, the !Xun and the Khwe. ï¿½The San of Platfonteinï¿½ is a collective name used for both the !Xun and Khwe. Short Biography: Carimbwe Katunga was born in 1958 in Mavinga, Angola and was employed by the Portuguese Military as a tracker in the 1970s. Katunga sees himself as a farmer and depict this in his artworks, he includes hunting, gathering and the making of traditional objects as part of the job of a farmer.',
