    'Plateelbakkerij Delft',
    '1913',
    'A Napoleonic War Dutch Plateelbakkerij Delft or Pottery Bakery Delft commemorative plate is one of a set consisting of 14 plates. The <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m064rk">pottery</a> that made these, although they had <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a>, a town in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a> in their name was made in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0k3p">Amsterdam</a>. Decorated in blue and red the plate commemorates all the leaders of the Netherlands between 1813 and 1913, startling with <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m098q8">King Willem I</a>, 1813-1840; <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0znyz">King Willem II</a> 1840-1849; <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0_0sy">King Willem III</a> 1849-1890; Regent Emma 1890-1898; <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0pxcz">Queen Wilhelmina</a> 1898 and her daughter Princess Juliana born 1909. In the center of the plate is a homage to being able to live the happy life of a civilian in Amsterdam. The plate was donated by Louise van Gybland Oosterhoff to the University of Pretoria in 1937.',
