    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m018ktp">Watercolor painting</a> by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italian</a> artist Giulio Falzoni (1900-1979) titled, San Romano, Lucca, created in 1945. The San Romano church in Lucca Italy consecrated in 1490. Short Biography: Giulio Falzoni was born in Mantua in Italy in 1900. He studied at the Academy of Fine Arts in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m031y2">Florence</a> and was a student of the Watercolorist, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h7l221">Plinio Nomellini</a> (1866-1943). In 1940, after visiting <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> he became attracted to the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> Watercolor style and also became a member of the London Society of Watercolorist. Falzoni is known as the last of the great Italian Watercolorists. This work was donated to the University of Pretoria by JA van Tilburg in 1980, who purchased the work from an exhibition held in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a> of the works of Giulio Falzoni, as well as his son Giordano (1925-1998). The Van Tilburg donation to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1980, included 125 Watercolors by Giulio Falzoni.',
