    'Unattributed',
    '1220/1290',
    'Archaeological <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> animal figurine probably depicts a small goat excavated from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, block 5, section 5, dating AD 1220 - AD 1290.The animal figurine has been hand-formed and pinched from a single piece of clay.The figure consists of four small pointed stubs for legs, tail, torso, neck, head and snout. The torso is well-rounded and extends into a neck and flattened head with an elongated pointed snout. The head is moulded in proportion to the torso. On the top of the head a protuberance is evident although not recognisable, possibly horns or ears. The legs are mere extensions of the torso and the animal stands on the pointed ends of the legs. The belly is characterised by a perforation at the right side just before the right, hind leg. The back side is flattened and short tail curves upward into a vertical position. This figurine (N317) forms part of the Mapungubwe National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of South Africa.',
