    'Pau Ten-Sen',
    '1985',
    'A portrait of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Christo Coetzee by the Japanese Gutai artist,Pau Ten-Sen. The work was created by Pau in Japan where he met Coetzee as part of the Gutai Group which was a radical post-war artist group founded in 1954. Coetzee was awarded a Japanese government bursary for two years of study in Osaka and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07dfk">Tokyo</a>, through mediation done by the British Council. The financial support was paid entirely in 1959. Francis King, later to become a respected writer, worked for the British Council in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09d4_">Kyoto</a> and was Coetzee''s liaison. Christo Coetzee arrival in Japan in February 1959, and was referred to the Gutai group of artists by professor J. Ijimi of Kyoto University. Coetzee had gained some knowledge of the group from Michel Tapiï¿½ and soon met founder Jiro Yoshihara and his son Michio Yoshihara. He would spend 11 months working with these important <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japanese</a> artists. Coetzee also made frequent trips to Tokyo, even taking a studio there. This work culminated in an exhibition of Informel works at the Minami Gallery, Tokyo in October 1959. In Tokyo he also met artist Takako Idemitsu and her husband Tono, an art critic. The Gutai group invited him to exhibit at the Takashimaya Gallery in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dqyw">Osaka</a> in 1960.',
