    'Austin Hleza',
    '1984',
    'A man on a tractor with chains by the Eswatini artist, Austin Hleza (1949-1997). Short Biography: Austin Hleza was born in 1949 in Mbuluzi, Eswatini (formerly known as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06v36">Swaziland</a>). Hleza was a self taught artist and was viewed as one of  Swaziland''s most important ceramic and graphic artists.  He was non-traditional by first becoming a male potter, traditionally a female artist''s role and he later developed new art forms within local Swazi cultural contexts.  Hleza trained at the Danish Pottery Development Centre and afterwards took over pottery production at Mantenga <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01mrgs">Craft</a> where he lectured at the National Handicrafts Training Centre in Mantenga.  During his later years, working from his combi studio he produced fine quality lino cuts specific to Swaziland rural and urban life.  He later  relocated to Ngwenya and continued to create a range of lino cuts, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramics</a> and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculptures</a> and has exhibited locally and internationally, where his works are found in galleries, private collections and museums. He passed away in Ngwenya in 1997.',
