    'Unattributed',
    '1030/1220',
    'Archaeological animal <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> figurine depicting the bos taurus species (cattle) excavated from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of K2, recovered from a burial KS. 6 No.8, dating AD 1030 - AD 1220.The figurine has been pinched from a rudimentary piece of clay and consists of tail,  two extensions for legs, torso, head with both ears and a snout with an apparent dewlap.The torso is flattened at the sides, however the back is rounded. The area between the ears is flattened; the face extends outward from this flattened area and curves into a pointed snout. The legs are mere extensions of the large torso and all four have been amalgamated into two flattened feet which allow the figurine to stand freely. The tail is rounded downward from the buttocks. The animal figurine is characterised by punctured, linear decoration along the spine and along the length and height of the torso which is considered an unusual feature in the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> clay figurine assemblage, as few animal clay figurines have such elaborate decoration.',
