    'Gerard de Leeuw',
    '1954',
    'A bronze <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> of a leopard by the South African artist Gerard de Leeuw (1912-1985). This <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01brf">bronze</a> was originally mounted on the wall at the Renzo Vignali Artistic Foundry in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> North, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> oldest art foundry, before it was brought to the University of Pretoria, after an attempted theft. Short Biography: Gerard de Leeuw was born in 1912 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0k3p">Amsterdam</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a> and studied in various places in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0154j">Belgium</a> and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>. He moved to South Africa in 1932 and opened a studio in Orange Grove, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> where he cast his own works if they were small enough. He passed away in Johannesburg in 1985.',
