(
    'Mike Edwards',
    '1987',
    'A bronze work titled Sundial by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artists Mike Edwards. Sundial is an instrument showing the time by the shadow of a pointer cast by the sun onto a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01brf">bronze</a> plate marked with the hours of the day. The sundial created by Edwards, rests on four small tortoises moving outward. The actual dial is inscribed with the Afrikaans words: Ek tel net die sonnige ure", translated in english as "I only count the sunny hours". The University of Pretoria''s coat of arms is also depicted on this sundial. There was once a little <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015p6">bird</a> sitting on the hand of the dial, unfortunately the work had been vandalised a few years back and the bird had gone missing. Short biography: Mike Edwards was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06f0y3">Port Elizabeth</a> South Africa in 1938. In 1991, he settled in the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02q2hg">Cradle of Humankind</a> area, north of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. He studied art initially at the Port Elizabeth Art School where he gained the National Art Teachers Certificate. He subsequently obtained a BA and MA in Fine Arts from the University of Pretoria. His first teaching post was in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c499">Bloemfontein</a> where he became Head of the Art Department and Vice-Principal of the then Technical College. <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rk0">In</a> 1973, he accepted a post as a lecturer at the University of Pretoria, later becoming Associate Professor of Fine Art. In 1990, he left teaching to become a full-time practicing artist. He has undertaken numerous visits overseas where has made a particular study of bronze as a medium for sculpture. These included foundries in America, the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">United Kingdom</a>, France and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italy</a> and the facility of Hermann Noack in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0156q">Berlin</a>. Edward received many commissions, including a 20m high stainless steel <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> in Pretoria, the Delville Wood Panel in Longueval, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>, and many portraits of public figures, academics and fellow artists. He has works in public buildings in South Africa such as the SA Medical  and Dental Council, State Theatre, Civitas and Momentum Life, all in Pretoria, and some provincial buildings of the Free State. Edwards has exhibited in group shows since 1959 in South Africa, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09c7w0">America</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>, and the UK. Edwards has a renowned artist''s career in portraiture with over 154 portraits completed spanning fifty years, 1958-2008. His iconic works are found in several notable collections in the University of Pretoria, University of the Free State, in the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> Art Museum, as well as in many private collections in South Africa and internationally.',
