    'Johann van der Schijff',
    '2001',
    'A sculpture titled, Walking the Line by the South African sculptor Johann van der Schijff (b.1969). In this work, Walking the Line is precariously close to toeing the line. This type of affectionate coercion is an inherent aspect of the aggression present in all socialization. It involves a process of conformity where adhering to societal norms is dangerously similar to conforming to those in power, which had catastrophic consequences during the apartheid era in South Africa. Short Biography: Johann van der Schijff is a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> sculptor born in 1969. He studied Fine Arts at the University of Pretoria and completed his Master''s degree in Fine Arts at the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. Van der Schijff''s <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculptures</a> often focus on the human form and its relationship to the natural environment. He is known for his use of bronze, which he sculpts using both traditional and contemporary techniques. In addition to his work as a sculptor, van der Schijff has also been involved in art education, serving as a lecturer at the Tshwane University of Technology in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. Van der Schijff''s art has been recognized with a number of awards and honors, including the PPC Imaginarium Award for sculpture in 2015 and the Tollman Award for the Visual Arts in 2016. He continues to create and exhibit his sculptures, exploring new forms and ideas in his work.',
