    'Paul Ramagaga',
    '1954',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m018ktp">watercolor painting</a> done in 1954 by the South African artist, Senthso Paul Ramagaga (1919-1995) titled, Stat meaning small rural village. The painting depicts the scene of a traditional <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> hut with two female figures sitting outside.  Short Biography: Senthso Paul Ramagaga was born in 1920 in Parys in the Free State where he lived with his grandmother on a farm  named Regina. He completed his schooling in Std Six at the Moroka Missionary Institute in Thabaï¿½Nchu and moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> in 1935, where he started to work for an art framing company. Ramagaga studied art only part-time under the tutelage of Rene Shapshak in Yeoville from 1948 to 1953. Ramagaga tutored several other artists in the following years, which included James Salang, Durant Sihlali and Ephraim Ngatane, all who later became well-known <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artists of the 1960s. Ramagaga passed away from a stroke on 12 September 1995.',
