    'A highly decorative tea spoon with enamel miniature of ''young woman in Russian folk dress'' dating to 1888 by the Russian Khlebnikov Factory. The spoon is made of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m025sf8x">silver</a>, champlevï¿½ <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tp42">enamel</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tp73">painted enamel</a>, casting, gilding. The Khlebnikov Factory was one of the leading Moscow <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0404d">jewellery</a> firms, a Partnership Ivan Khlebnikov, Sons and Co who  produced the most diverse products: from silverware to interior decorations of the Kremlin cathedrals.This type of spoon decoration was very popular during the last years of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03pn33">Khlebnikov</a> Factory which moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04swd">Moscow</a> in 1871, but later closed down  during the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06fby">Russian Revolution in 1917</a>.',
