    'A Still Life with flowers by the Hungarian artist Eszter Mattioni (1902-1993). In June 1950 the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> held an exhibition of modern Hungarian artists. The exhibition itself was hailed as a huge success by the Newspapers. The works on the exhibition was called naï¿½ve, honest and fresh. The Still life with <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">flowers</a> was donated to the University by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03gj2">Hungarians</a> after the exhibition. Short Biography: Eszter Mattioni was born in Szekszï¿½rd Hungary in 1902. She studied at the Applied Arts Vocational School In Hungary and is today seen as one of the most prominent Hungarian female artists of the 20th Century. She became a member of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06g9p8">Pï¿½l Szinyei Merse</a> Society in Hungary in 1946 at the height of her career. Today her works is very highly acclaimed and in the possession of art collections like the Pompidou and the Hungarian National Art Gallery in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m095w_">Budapest</a>. She passed away in Budapest in 1993.',
