    'An <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m011lx">acrylic</a> on canvas painting titled, The Big Move by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Lelani Nicolaisen (b.1988). The artist usually paints from life experience and what she observes with a focus subject on landscapes. The Big Move was inspired by the relocation and movement of the iconic painting, "The Discovery of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06npx">sea</a> route circumnavigating <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">Africa</a> by the artist Alexis Preller. This painting is 13m in length comprising of several large panels. In 2020,  the artwork was moved from exhibition at the Javett Art Centre in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> to the Villa Gallery on the University of Pretoria Hatfield Campus. The large painting was literally carried by several curators, conservators, other museum staff and assistants across Lynnwood Road for about a kilometer to its new location in the University of Pretoria Museums. Short Biography: Lelani Nicolaisen was born in 1988. In 2006, she won a fashion design competition with Bernina and the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c499">Bloemfontein</a> Fashion Academy and received a bursary the following year to study <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02qqd4n">fashion design</a>  After completing fashion design, Nicolaisen graduated in 2011 with a BA Fine Arts degree at the University of Pretoria. In 2012, Nicolaisen represented the University of Pretoria in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09tlh">Nottingham</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02jx1">England</a>, where she exhibited some of her works as part of the first World Event Young Artists Programme. Nicolaisen studied further, completing a MA in Fine Arts at the University of Pretoria, in 2017 was the recipient of an NRF grantholder-linked bursary from 2015- 2016. Nicolaisen served as guest lecturer in the Department of Fine Arts at the School of Arts  at the University of Pretoria from 2015 onwards. She has multiple artworks in the University of Pretoria permanent art collection and the Art Bank of South Africa acquired one of her works in 2019. Nicolaisen is also known for her <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m012z_m">installation art</a> and has participated in many group art exhibitions in South Africa, including at Nirox Sculpture Park, Fried Contemporary, the Pretoria Art Museum and Pretoria Association of Arts. Nicolaisen is interested in multi-sensorial art and how the audience may become immersed within art environments. Nicolaisen participated in the International Curatorial Program (2020 - 2021) and completed the Inclusive Curatorial Practices: Accessibility, Representation and Diversity Program (2022 - 2023) offered in  <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>, Europe. From 2019 to May 2023, she worked as the Curator of Art Exhibitions and Galleries at the University of Pretoria. She is currently a practising artist and a freelance curator based in the Western Cape.',
