    'Small human clay figurine excavated from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of K2, test trench 3, block A2 dating approximately AD 1030 - AD 1220.The diminutive figurine consists of two legs, buttocks, torso, left arm and neck. The human figurine has been moulded from a single body of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a>. The two inverted cone shaped legs end in a rounded buttocks with steatopygia features. The buttocks are clearly divided by an incised line defining the two cheeks. The legs are dwarfed in comparison to the torso. The elongated torso is cylindrical and ends in a stubby, left arm which extends outwards at the base of the neck. The neck/head is triangular and protrudes vertically. The figurine is characterised by its small size and a small puncture hole at the base of the neck.',
