    'Isaac Seoka',
    '2023',
    'A carved <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wooden</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06npx">sea</a> creature with tentacles and large eyes,  probably an octopus titled, Hardships (2023) by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Isaac (Sakie) Seoka (b.1967). The carved wooden <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> is produced from the Searsia lancea the karee or red karee <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">tree</a> that occurs from <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m088vb">Zambia</a> in the north to the Western Cape in the south.  The word karee is said to be the original Khoi word for mead. as the fruit from the tree are edible and were once used as an important ingredient of mead or honey beer.  This work by Seoka was purchased from a University of Pretoria fine arts staff exhibition titled, Textured Surfaces in 2023. Short Biography: Isaac Seoka was born in Venda in 1967. In the 1980s, he became the sculpture studio assistant at the Department of Fine Arts at the University of Pretoria and he continues an artist working in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> and contributes his works to several group exhibitions.',
