    'Unattributed',
    '1789/1925',
    'A glazed Persian Qajar Dynasty (1789 to 1925) by an unattributed artist. The 19th century, square <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramic tile</a> decorated with the portrait of a Persian nobleman surrounded with floral detail. Qajar art refers to the art, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03nfmq">architecture</a>, and art forms of the Qajar dynasty, which lasted from 1781 to 1925 in Iran, former Persia. Traditionally, Qajar tiles were made of redstone paste, moulded and painted with transparent glaze. Such tiles were mainly produced in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ftlx">Tehran</a>, the Qajar capital, where several friezes of rectangular underglaze-painted tiles such as this example, were common in nineteenth-century Persian architecture.',
