    'Esias Bosch',
    '1980',
    'A large vitrified and laminated stoneware wall tile with still-life of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">flowers</a> by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist, Esias Bosch (1923-2010). Bosch is a pioneer South African studio potter, whose oeuvre was influenced by the Anglo-Oriental tradition. Bosch explored all ceramic mediums from earthenware, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03q7p08">stoneware</a> to porcelain and in about 1988 he began to work and experiment on large flat imposing surfaces. Bosch expressed his love of decorating and painting on an open flat surface and often produced very large beautiful colour in sizes up to 1.6 metres. He discovered ways of producing very large and extremely thin vitrified wall tiles decorated with multiple layers of underglaze ceramic stains and fired several times.                                                                                                                                                        <br/>Short biography: Esias Bosch was born on July 11, 1923, in  Winburg in the Free State Province of South Africa. He studied art at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> School of Art. After completing his studies in 1946, he was awarded a scholarship to study ceramics in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a>. He left for England in 1949 and served his apprenticeship with two of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02jx1">Englandï¿½s</a> most famous potters, Raymond Finch and Michael Cardew. Bosch returned to South Africa in 1953 to head the ceramics department of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a> Art School. After two years in Durban, Bosch and his young family moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> where he worked in the medium of earthenware. Bosch received numerous awards in South Africa, including the Oude Libertas Award and a medal of honour by the South African Academy for Science and Art and the Chancellorï¿½s <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m020yd1">Medal</a> from the University of Pretoria. Bosch also held international fame. In 1963 he was awarded a silver medal by the Smithsonian Institute in the Ninth International Exhibition of Ceramic Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0rh6k">Washington DC</a> and was invited to enter work for the prestigious International Ceramics Exhibition at the Victoria and Albert Museum in 1972 and in 1983. He also held a very successful exhibition of large lustre tiles in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03pbf">Hanover</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>. One of the tiles was purchased by the Keramion Museum in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01v8c">Cologne</a> for their international collection of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramics</a>. Bosch died on April 24, 2010 at the age of 86.',
