    'Zulu Bidi',
    '1975',
    'A pastel drawing titled, Tiger by the South African artist Zulu Bidi (1945-2001). The artwork was originally intended as an album cover for his <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_d0">jazz</a> music, but it was probably never used as such. Short Biography: Zulu Bibi was born on 13 March 1945 and lived in Soweto for most of his life. He did not finish formal schooling: with two younger sisters to put through school, he became breadwinner, earning their school fees through informal trading. He fell in love with music early, singing with the close-harmony Jazz Voices and turned to art very late in his life. His first instrument was a piano he brought home on a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03k3r">horse</a> and cart. Bidi was first known as Bassist, Jazz musician.  Probably best known since the 2011 , he was the bassist  and cover artist for the popular Soweto band, Batsumi. His bass-playing stretched across genres, and also included work on Tete Mbambisaï¿½s audaciously modernist Did You Tell Your Mother and a whole range of other music born mainly in and around <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0710ps">Orlando</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0729t">Soweto</a>. He also designed the cover album, Night in Pelican by Abacothozi which was Batsumi''s self-titled album. His life and work featured in a BBC-TV-commissioned documentary, Life and Death in Soweto.  In 1977, together with other <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artists such as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0gx02sn">David Koloane</a> and Hugh Notshulungu, Bidi started the first black owned art gallery in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. He also taught himself to design and hand-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01mrgs">craft</a> footwear. Bidi passed away in 2001.',
