(
    'Jean Kotze-Louw',
    '1980',
    'A lithograph titled, Kya Rosa by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Jean Kotze-Louw (1929-2014). The work was done for the 50th celebration of the founding of the University of Pretoria in 1980. In 1930, the University changed from being  the Tranvsaal University College (TUC or Tuks) to the University of Pretoria. The building is an interpretation of the first photograph of the first University building known popularly as Kya Rosa, a  Late Victorian house today situated at the University of Pretoria entrance. The original building was constructed in Skinner Street in 1895 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> and belonged to Leo Weinthal, owner of The Press a forerunner of Pretoria News.  The house was named after his wife, Rosa. The word ï¿½Kyaï¿½ is the Zulu word for ï¿½houseï¿½. Kya Rosa later became the first home of the then Transvaal University College (TUC) , but by 1915 it was no longer in use. In 1980, the University commissioned the construction of a replica of the house where it stands today ï¿½ at the Roper Street entrance to the University of Pretoria. Work began in 1983, under the guidance of architect Albrecht Holm, an alumnus of UP. Precise measurements were taken from the original building and old photographs were used as reference to ensure that the reconstructed building closely resembles the original house. Many of the original Victorian fittings were used in the reconstruction. Kya Rosa was officially opened by Dr Anton Rupert on 25 October 1985. Short Biography: Jean Kotze-Louw was born in 1929 in Lichtenburg in the North West Province. She studied fine arts from 1947 to 1951 at the University of Natal and after winning the Emma Smith Scholarship in 1950, she continued her studies in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italy</a>, and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>. Between 1958 and 1960, she commenced her career as an academic lecturer in mosaic at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01ybj9">Positano</a> Art Workshop in Italy. In 1975,  she became a lecturer of Visual Design and Painting at the University of Pretoria. Kotze-Louw passed away in 2014.',
