    'Willem Brouwer',
    '1913',
    'A Dutch commemorative Napoleonic war plate glazed with a characteristic black tin glaze is a typical creation of the Dutch ceramicist Willem Coenraad Brouwer (1877-1933). He was the owner and ceramic maker at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0wbfy">Leiderdorp</a> Vredelust factory that was viewed as the pinnacle producer of Art Nouveau and Art Deco ceramics outside of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0pvxd">Gouda</a> in The Netherlands. The plate celebrates 100 years (1813-1913) of Independence of The Netherlands after the Napoleonic Wars and depicts the Dutch <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m096mb">Lion</a> and a rising sun. The back is partially glazed and has the Brouwer stamp and numerals stamped in clay.',
