    'George Enslin',
    '1951',
    'Worcester Landscape is a painting by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> / <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist George Enslin (1919-1972) painted in 1951. The painting shows Worcester in the Western Cape Province. The work was donated by Enslin after his 1951 exhibition at the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, an exhibition that was the last at the then MacFadyen Memorial Hall, the heart of Art Exhibitions in the North of South Africa. Short Biography: George Enslin was born in 1919 in Richmond <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02jx1">England</a> but immigrated at a young age to South Africa in 1920. He studies in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a> under the tutelage of Maurice van Essche but also in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> and Carrara. He travelled to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japan</a> more than six times and marries a Japanese lady, something frowned upon by the South African government at the time. Due to this he immigrated to Aegina, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m035qy">Greece</a> in 1967  where he passes away in 1972.',
