    'Barbara Tyrrell',
    '1983',
    'Bhaca by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Artist and author Dr Barbara Eleanor Harcourt Tyrrell (1912-2015).  In the painting, a Bhaca (people of the Zulu region near Richmond in Natal became a favourite Tyrrell subject matter) matron attends to a young wife''s hair, a head cloth of respect is tied in place afterwards. The painting, one of a series of 59 in the collection were done by Tyrrell for her book African Heritage in 1983.Tyrrell, along with being an artist was a lifelong scholar in studying <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> rituals and clothing of the people of South Africa also wrote several books on the subject. The University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> bought the collection from Tyrrell in 1988. Tyrrell is known internationally for her detailed costume studies of the traditional dress of the indigenous peoples of southern Africa. Tyrrell was born on 15  March 1912 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a>, South Africa. Her father, who died while she was a small child, had occupied the post of assistant magistrate and later interpreter in the Department of Native Affairs and had been stationed in various Natal towns, his final posting being to Eshowe, Zululand. Tyrrell''s grandfather was Frederick Fynney, interpreter and companion to the Zulu king <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02j_6f">Cetshwayo</a> during the latter''s visit to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cw10">Queen Victoria</a> in 1882. Tyrrell trained as an artist at the former University of Natal during the 1930''s, when the fine arts department was still linked with that of the former Technical College. Tyrrell was 103 years old when she passed away in 2015.',
