(
    'Guilio Falzoni',
    '1945',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m018ktp">watercolour painting</a> by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italian</a> artist Giulio Falzoni (1900-1979) titled, Street Scene in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0fhsz">Naples</a> done in 1945. The painting was completed where Francesco Caracciolo Street is today, overlooking the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06npx">sea</a> and in the far distance is the residential quarters of Posillipo. Giulio Falzoni was born in Mantua in Italy in 1900. He studied at the Academy of Fine Arts in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m031y2">Florence</a> and was a student of the watercolourist, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h7l221">Plinio Nomellini</a> (1866-1943). <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rk0">In</a> 1940, after visiting <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> he became attracted to the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> watercolour style and also became a member of the London Society of watercolourist. Falzoni is known as the last of the great Italian watercolourists. This work was donated to the University of Pretoria by JA van Tilburg in 1980, who purchased the work from an exhibition held in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a> of the works of Giulio Falzoni, as well as his son Giordano (1925-1998). The Van Tilburg donation to the UNiversity of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1980, included 125 watercolours by Giulio Falzoni.',
