    'A 1900 war propaganda <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015ll">board game</a> named "Boer and Rooinek Spel" is an edition by the Brothers Koster in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0k3p">Amsterdam</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a>. The game of goose or gezelschapsspel was drawn by EG Schlette, an unknown French comic artist. The game board is pro-Boer war propaganda highlighting the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0bqtx">South African War</a> (1899-1902) and the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> failures during the first phase of the war. The Afrikaans term, "Rooinek",  literally meaning "Redneck" was a jocular name (now considered an offensive term) was used specifically for the English-speaking British soldiers during the First Boer War (1880-1881). They never wore appropriate headgear, so their skin on the back of their necks became easily sunburnt and red from the African sun. Two portraits with a ribbon of numbered boxes walking over the contours of their headwears and over their chest. On the left of the game is an English soldier depicted with a helmet and on the right, a Boer or <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> farmer with red beard. In the undermaster, are the rules of the game laid out in seven columns in Dutch.',
