    'Unattributed',
    '1030/1220',
    'Archaeological <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> figurine fragment of a female torso excavated in the 1930s from the South African Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of K2, block 1.2., section 13, 20 dating approximately AD 1030 - AD 1220.The torso is elongated and cylindrical extending from just below the waist to above the arms. Two breasts are positioned just below the arch of the armpits. The arms are presented as two stubby protrusions. The front of the figurine is decorated by an incised arch-like protuberance at the bottom of the torso. Decoration in the form of dotted lines extends from the frontal arched protuberance around to the back of the torso. Additionally two, vertical, dotted lines are apparent on the back, drawn from buttocks upwards.This figurine (N295) forms part of the Mapungubwe National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a>.',
