(
    'Maud Sumner',
    '1943',
    'Bertha Hagart by South African artist, Maud Frances Eyston Sumner (1902-1985). A work depicting a female seated figure reading a book. This seated figure is of Bertha Hagart, a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> pianist in the 1940s. This work was first exhibited at the Macfadyen Memorial Hall at the University of Pretoria in 1943. Anton Hendriks renamed the work, ï¿½The Readerï¿½ during the exhibition opening. Sumner donated the work to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1984. Short Biography: Sumner was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> and spent her formative years in her hometown. After matriculating in South Africa she went to Oxford to study Literature in 1922 where she obtained her master''s degree. After that she studied painting at the Westminster School of Arts. In 1926 Sumner moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> to study at the L''Acadï¿½mie de la Grande Chaumiï¿½re in the Montparnasse district. She was highly influenced by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m058q3r">Maurice Denis</a> and George Desvalliï¿½res. Her first solo exhibition was held at Galerie Druet in Paris in 1932. Sumner was diagnosed with a peculiar nerve disorder known as Guillaume Barrï¿½ syndrome whilst in Paris in 1978. She opted to return to South Africa to continue her work as an artist and poet up until her death in 1985 at her home in Johannesburg.',
