    'This work titled The Waterhole is by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0j4b">Angolan</a> / <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Carimbwe Katunga (b.1958). The work shows several antelope gathering along with a scorpion, a frog and a lizard. Katunga was part of the Platfontein Art Group, a relocated community of !Xu and Khwe people displaced from Angola during the wars of the 1970s and 1980s. They were resettled at Platfontein near Schmidtsdrift outside <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjpx">Kimberley</a> in South Africa and in the 1990s the community were resettled again at Wildebeeskuil. The community consists of two San tribes, the !Xun and the Khwe. ï¿½The San of Platfonteinï¿½ is a collective name used for both the !Xun and Khwe. Short Biography: Carimbwe Katunga was born in 1958 in Mavinga, Angola and was employed by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05r4w">Portuguese</a> Military as a tracker in the 1970s. Katunga sees himself as a farmer and depict this in his artworks, he includes hunting, gathering and the making of traditional objects as part of the job of a farmer.',
