    'An unidentified <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m025rs2z">gold</a> fragment of some animal form which has been highly decorated with chevron lines and raised areas indicative of eyes and ears. The form displays minor lacunae, nail perforations and evidence of material loss.  Originating from the archaeological site of Mapungubwe Hill, associated with the original gold grave burial (M1 A620) dating from CE 1250 to CE 1290.  This fragment is  part of specifically declared National Heritage Mapungubwe Collection in South Africa. Originating from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, associated with the original burial dating from CE 1250 to CE 1290.  The archaeological landscape of Mapungubwe in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a> was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2003. The Mapungubwe Collection is stewarded under the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, where the archaeological collection is on public exhibition for the purposes of research and education.',
