    'Willem de Sanderes Hendrikz',
    '1941',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01brf">bronze</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> titled, Zulu by the South African sculptor Willem de Sanderes Hendrikz (1910-1959). In 1941, Hendrikz commissioned by Prof Raymond Dart the Anthropologist to create portrait works depicting the heads of the San, Khoi, Pondo, Swazi, Shangaan,  Shona and a Zulu people, seven in total for the Anatomy Museum at the Witwatersrand University in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. It is unknown if the museum ever acquired copies despite the commission, however in 1948 Dr. G Bï¿½chner, on whose farm Hendrikz had his art studio, bought the set of African head portraits. They were set up in his home next to the swimming pool. Over the years, the heads was exhibited by Hendrikz (loaning them from Bï¿½chner). The head of the Shangaan was exhibited in December 1947 at Christieï¿½s Art Gallery and the Mashona, at the Exhibition of Contemporary South African Paintings, Drawings and Sculpture in 1948 at the Tate Gallery in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a>.  At most, Hendrikz works were only cast once or twice and are exceedingly rare with only this bronze Zulu as part of the collection of the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. Short Biography: Willem de Sanderes Hendrikz was born in 1910 in Brandfort in the Free State. As a young boy, he studied under the German artist, Fritz Hickman. In 1928,  studied architecture at the University of the Witwatersrand and took sculpture lessons at the Johannesburg Technical College. In July 1934, Hendrikz took part in his first major exhibition at the Cooling Gallery in London. After his return to South Africa, he got <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04ztj">married</a> and began practising sculpture as a full-time artist in Johannesburg. In 1935, he was given his first commission to create the panels for the Red Cross House in Johannesburg. In 1937, he became a lecturer at the University of the Witwatersrand and in 1940 Hendrikz joined the South African forces in North <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">Africa</a> during the Second World War and was reportedly responsible for the creation of camouflage during the war. After the war, he returned to South Africa and continued a career as a full-time sculptor. During his lifetime, Hendrikz was flagged by art critics as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africaï¿½s</a> next great sculptor, but due to war circumstances and ill health, Hendrikz did not create more works. Hendrikz died in 1959 in Plettenberg Bay at the young age of 49. This Zulu sculpture was purchased from Mr CI Rautenbach in 2009 who had bought it directly from Dr G Bï¿½chner, who in turn bought it from artist.',
