    'Unattributed',
    '1220/1290',
    'Archaeological <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> animal figurine depicting a sheep (ovis aries) excavated from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, block 6, section 1, dating AD 1220 - AD 1290.The animal figurine has been pinched from a single piece of clay. The figurine consists of three simplified, pointed stubs for legs, an udder, tail, torso, neck, head and snout. This clay figurine clearly represents a female sheep or ewe with a small dewlap from the rear jaw to the throat and the udder is depicted as a single mass hanging beneath the stomach comprising of pairs of mammary glands with protruding teats. A dewlap was pinched running downward from the snout to between the two front legs. The torso is rounded and the neck extends upward into the head. The pointed snout extends straight and downward from the flattened forehead. The legs are mere extensions of the torso and are formed in such a way as to allow for the figurine to free stand. The tail curves downward from the buttocks of the animal. The exploitation of livestock such as sheep (ovis aries) is common among Iron Age farmer communities in southern <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">Africa</a> as they were introduced two millennia ago.',
