    'Hezekiel Ntuli',
    '1941',
    'A large male bust (1941) titled, Zulu iNduna by the South African sculptor <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g11nnv5zr9q">Hezekiel Ntuli</a> (1912-1973).  An iNduna is a Zulu chief , headman or  traditional councillor. The portrait is of an unknown Zulu male. Short Biography: Ntuli was born in the Eshowe district of KwaZulu Natal in 1912 and was educated at a mission station near Entumeni, followed by two years of schooling in Pietermaritzburg. In the 1930''s, he sold handmade clay sculptures in the city centre, where Mr. Stanley Williams appreciated his works and purchased them for the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01_vrh">Pietermaritzburg</a> Museum in Kwazulu Natal. In 1931 , over 71 of Ntuliï¿½s sculptures were donated to the Natal Museum, making him one of the first black artists in KwaZulu-Natal to be identifiable by his own name in a public collection. Williams became Ntuliï¿½s first art patron and mentor, facilitating his indenture with the Department of Native Affairs to continue make clay <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculptures</a>. Ntuli''s work gradually became internationally recognised and sold his art from Johannesburg to Germany. Ntuli held several exhibitions at the SA Academy Exhibition in 1932 in Johannesburg and later again in 1936 his works featured at the Empire Exhibition in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. His works travelling internationally in 1966 to the Museum fï¿½r Volkekunde at <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g7pm">Kiel</a> University in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>. Ntuli''s works are found in many <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> collections such as the Killie Campbell Collections at the University of Natal, the National Cultural History Museum in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, the; Zululand Historical Museum in Eshowe, the Natal Museum in Pietermaritzburg and at the University of Pretoria.  Ntuli won an award in 1930,  First Prize at the Royal Agricultural Show in Natal. Ntuli passed away in 1973 in Mlalazi in Kwazulu Natal.',
