    'Unattributed',
    '1220/1290',
    'Archaeological <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> figure of a bull excavated in in the 1930s from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, Mahobi trench JS 1, dating AD 1220 - AD 1290.The figurine has been produced by the pinched method formed from a single piece of clay. The animal figurine consists of 4 pointed stubs for legs, torso, head, ears and snout. The torso is rounded, however due to material loss, the exact form is not recognisable. At the joining of head and torso, a protruding hump is evident suggestive of an adult male bull of the species bos taurus (cattle). The head is characterised by a two ears which extend horizontally from the sides of the head. The area between the ears is flattened and the face curves slightly outward and falls vertically downward into a pointed snout. The legs are mere extensions of the torso and the animal stands on the pointed ends of the legs. The back side is flattened and no distinguishable tail is apparent.  .',
