    'An archaeological clay figurine depicting a giraffe from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, from the base area known as the southern Terrace, block 8, section 6, dating approximately from AD 1220 - AD 1290. The giraffe figurine has been hand-formed and pinched from a single piece of raw clay.  The clay figurine depicts a typical giraffe with a long tubular neck and four spread leds, with a curled tail on its rump, this is usually indicative of a running giraffe.This is a unique figurine from the Mapungubwe clay figurine assemblage as it is a depiction of a wild animal, as many of the other figurines are domestic <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0jbk">animals</a>. The giraffe (camelopardalis giraffa) is an <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> artiodactyl <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04rky">mammal</a> and the tallest living terrestrial mammal, rock art of the Mapungubwe area also depict giraffe figures.',
