    'Unattributed',
    '1220/1290',
    'An archaeological animal clay figurine from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, from the base known as the southern Terrace, from excavation Square K8, layer 7, dating approximately from AD 1220 - AD 1290.The figurine has been hand-formed and pinched from a single piece of clay. The figurine most probably depicts a sheep (ovis aries) and has  four pointed stubs for legs, an udder, torso, neck, head, right ear and snout. The torso is rounded and elongated and extends from tail to head in a curved line. The neck is elongated and cylindrical and ends in a very small, flattened head. The head is characterised by a right ear or horn. The area between the horns is flattened and the face falls vertically downward into a pointed snout. The neck curves outward and downward toward the front legs. The udder is positioned between the hind legs and two teats are apparent. The back side is flattened and no tail is evident however there are two perforations on the back rump. The legs are mere extensions of the torso and the animal possibly stood on the pointed ends of the legs, however free standing is no longer possible due to missing parts at the right, front leg. This figurine (N316) forms part of the Mapungubwe National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of South Africa.',
