    'Hezekiel Ntuli',
    '1940',
    'A large bust titled Bushman on the back by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> sculptor <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g11nnv5zr9q">Hezekiel Ntuli</a> (1912-1973). The work is of a very old man from the Bushmen in Eshowe. Today the word Bushman is seen as a bit of a political conundrum as the acceptable word by the South African Government is San but the people of this group prefer the name Bushman. Short Biography: Born in the Eshowe district of KwaZulu Natal in 1912, Ntuli was educated at a mission station near Entumeni and later for a couple of years in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01_vrh">Pietermaritzburg</a>. In the 1930''s he was selling his sculptures in the city centre where a man shaw his works and purchased them for the Pietermaritzburg museum. After that his works became internationally recognised and sold from <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>. He passed away in 1973 in Mlalazi.',
