    'Isaac Seoka',
    '2011',
    'At the entrance to the University of Pretoria in University Road, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> South Africa is a large installation fountain feature titled, "Swimming against the Current". The work depicts 34 <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ch_cf">fish</a> swimming upstream by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> sculptor, Isaac (Sakkie) Seoka (b.1967) from the University of Pretoria. Fish IV was one of the marquettes for the commission of the fountain. Short Biography:  Isaac Seoka was born in 1967 in Venda and as an artist began carving his works in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wood</a>. Another South African sculptor and colleague, Guy du Toit (b.1958) assisted him in making the wax works for casting into bronze. This work was created with the idea of the fish as a symbol of knowledge, swimming upstream to gain new knowledge. According to Seoka, the university serves as an institution and fountain of knowledge where students must swim against the current of today, in order to achieve a better future.',
