    'Christo Coetzee',
    '1984',
    'Woven Abstract is a painting by South African artist Christo Coetzee (1929-2000). This work was made for an Avante Garde exhibition in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ftkx">Taipei</a> Fine Arts Museum in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06f32">Taiwan</a> in 1985. Short Biography: The <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> born artist, Christo Coetzee (1929-2000) pursued his art studies at the Slade School of Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> as a complementary tuition exercise to his fine art degree qualification acquired from the University of the Witwatersrand. Then most of his works of art were mainly stylized figurative images and still lifes. Subsequent to that he moved to Europe on an Government Travelling Scholarship becoming part of the Stadler Stable in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> before moving to Finestrat <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06mkj">Spain</a>. Later he also went to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japan</a> where he was invited to join the Gutai Group, the first radical Art Group in post war Japan. There he developed his later art style that ultimately classified him as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> leading and prominent avant-garde artist. Coetzee received international recognition for his contribution to the avant-garde art movements known as Art Informel, Assemblage and Neo-Baroque in Paris, Spain and Japan during the 1950s and 1960s, an art style he perfected. He passed away at the age of 71 in 2000 in Tulbagh in the Cape.',
