    'An <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03yhk">ink</a> on <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0641k">Paper</a> of a white rhinoceros, simply titled, Rhino  painted in the 1960s is by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Zakkie Eloff (1925-2003). Short Biography: Zacharias (Zakkie) Eloff was born in 1925 in Namibia. He studied under the South African artist, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c4l7x">Walter Battiss</a> in High School and later at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> Technical College and later completed his studies at the University of Pretoria. From 1962 to 1968, he worked as a game ranger in the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01_w45">Etosha National Park</a> in Namibia, where his love of painting the unique desert <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05bmq">Namibian</a> landscape began. In 1969, Eloff settled in the Eastern Transvaal with his wife Rene Eloff and where Eloff passed away in 2003.',
