(
    'Christo Coetzee',
    '1995',
    'This oil on Board painting is titled, Voltaire as Arab is by the South African artist Christo Coetzee (1929-2000) created in 1995. Coetzee depicts  Voltaire who was better known as Francois-Marie Arouet (1694-1778) in Arab attire. Voltaire was a French writer, historian and philosopher famous for his advocacy of civil liberties and freedom of religion in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>. In his portrayal of Voltaire as an Arab, Coetzee passes political commentary of his impression Voltaire in the Arab world would encourage social, political and religious freedom. Short biography. The Johannesburg born artist, Christo Coetzee pursued his art studies at the Slade School of Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> as a complementary tuition exercise to his fine art degree qualification acquired from the University of the Witwatersrand in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> South Africa. Most of Coetzee''s works are mainly colourful, stylized figurative images and still lifes. After completing his studies he moved to Europe on an Government Travelling Scholarship  and become part of the Stadler Stable in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> before moving to Finestrat in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06mkj">Spain</a>. Later, Coetzee went to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japan</a> where he was invited to join the Gutai Group, the first radical Art Group in post-war Japan. It was in Japan that Coetzee developed his later art style that ultimately classified him as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> leading and prominent avant-garde artists. Coetzee received international recognition for his contribution to the avant-garde art movements known as Art Informel, Assemblage and Neo-Baroque in Paris, Spain and Japan during the 1950s and 1960s, an art style he perfected. He passed away at the age of 71 in 2000 in Tulbagh in the Cape and bequeathed his entire home and collection to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>.',
