    'Alexis Preller',
    '1946',
    'Studio Interior, Yggdrasil by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Alexis Preller (1911-1975) was donated to the University of Pretoria after an exhibition in the Macfadyen Memorial Hall in 1946. The painting was created after the artist''s interior of his studio which he named Yggdrasil. The artist''s colour palette is recognisable in the work as you see the blue green colours typical of his oeuvre. The sun <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">flowers</a> in the foreground are a tribute to the artist <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07_m2">Vincent van Gogh</a>. The painting is in Preller''s typical surrealist style and takes the viewer on a journey through the artist''s imaginary world. Prellerï¿½s studio was so important to him that he named it ï¿½Yggdrasilï¿½. The word Yggdrasil means ï¿½World <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">Tree</a>ï¿½ or ï¿½Tree of Lifeï¿½, as it refers to the cycle of birth, growth, death and rebirth. As with the significant meaning of his studioï¿½s name, the objects Preller painted are also loaded with metaphysical significance. Short biography: Preller was born in Pretoria in 1911. Preller''s home and studio was designed by the architect Norman Eaton in 1944 on Preller''s Farm near Broederstroom. Preller died on the farm in 1975. Norman Eaton also designed <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09n5cb">Anton van Wouw</a> home in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>.',
