    'A painting by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Velaphi Mzimba (1959-2021) titled "The Boer" meaning the Farmer done in 1996. Mzimba''s work, like this one, focuses on the eye and the stare that the work gives. The word "Boer" was used during the Apartheid era as a term for the oppressor, as land and land ownership played a critical role in the Struggle. The artist also uses the term Boer, which is an Afrikaans word, to lift out another point that played a hard and bitter part of the Struggle, which is the matter of language. Language was at the center of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07s6rd">Soweto Uprising</a> in June 1976, a key event in Apartheid history. Short Biography: Velaphi Mzimba was born in 1959 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0729t">Soweto, Johannesburg</a>. In 1975 he joined the Mofolo Art Centre and studied under Dan Rakgoathe. His first one man show was in 1981 in the Carlton Hotel, where he exhibited paintings with an anti apartheid theme. He passed away on 24 June 2021 of COVID-19 related complications.',
