    'Ferrie Binge-Coetzee',
    '1994',
    'Titled, Birdï¿½s Nest is a work by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Ferrie Binge Coetzee (1926-2010) created in 1994. Painted with oils and a granular substance, the work shows a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015p6">birdï¿½s</a> nest full of sticks and even small bones, with tiny animal skulls visible within the subject matter covered in bird droppings. Short biography: Ferrie Francina Binge-Coetzee was born in 1926 in Keetmanshoop in South West Africa (today <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05bmq">Namibia</a>). She studied at the Haagsch Akademie voor Beeldende Kunsten in 1953 under the tutelage of Randi Doorman. In 1968, she <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04ztj">married</a> fellow artist Christo Coetzee and settled in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0zc6">Alicante</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06mkj">Spain</a>. Binge-Coetzee as an artist was overshadowed by the iconic fame of her husband and rarely received the same attention in the media. About her art and a critique of her wild colour used, she once said ï¿½Have you ever seen how the wild <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c9ph5">flowers</a> arrange themselvesï¿½ so as to suggest that painting with lose abundance was natural. Binge-Coetzee tragically died in an apartment fire in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a> in 2010.',
