    'Stanley Pinker',
    '1992',
    'A painting by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Stanley Pinker. The painting Kos is op die Tafel (Dinner is served), painted in 1992, refers to the Afrikaans idiom meaning that the meal is ready. The work shows a white man seated at a table with his knife and fork in his hands, ready to eat.  On the table in front of him there is a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02dl1y">hat</a>.  Most likely this refers to the saying `Iï¿½d rather eat my hatï¿½.  Next to the man there is a black man serving bones.   The black man is dressed like a servant, but is actually standing behind a screen on which the figure of a servant is painted. If one looks at the servantï¿½s feet, one notices that he is wearing a pair of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06rrc">shoes</a> that appear to be more expensive than those worn by the man at the table. In the background there are empty boxes.  Everything seems to point to a lack of money. The painting has a strong political message and it attempts to give a visual impression of the fear in the white community preceding the change of government in South Africa in 1994.',
