    'Caiphas Nxumalo',
    '1976',
    'An etching by the South African artist Caiphas Nxumalo (1940-2002) titled Umbus Omusha Kwazulu. The work was done in 1971 because of the coronation of King Goodwill Zwelithini (1949-2021) of the Zulu on 3 December 1971. Short Biography: Born in 1940 in the Msinga district of KwaZulu Natal, Caiphas Nxumalo was a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist known for his distinctive style of painting that combined traditional <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> patterns and motifs with modern elements. Born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a>, Nxumalo was exposed to a rich cultural heritage from an early age and was influenced by the vibrant local art scene. His work has been featured in numerous exhibitions in South Africa and abroad, and has won critical acclaim for its powerful use of color, form, and texture. Nxumalo''s paintings are inspired by the natural beauty of South Africa, as well as by the rich cultural traditions of his homeland. Through his work, he aimed to preserve and celebrate the unique cultural heritage of his country and to share its beauty with the world.',
