    'Richard Findlay',
    '1990',
    'An etching of five animals endemic to sub-Saharan Africa by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> illustrator and artist Richard (Dick) Findlay (1928-1996). The work is a page of plate 22 used in the second edition of the book by Skinner, J.D. and Smithers, R.H.N., 1990. "The Mammals of the Southern African Sub-Region" (University of Pretoria Press). The page contains works depicting the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> Striped Weasel; Striped (African) Polecat; Honey Badger, Spotted-necked Otter and the Cape Clawless Otter. Short Biography: Richard (Dick Findlay) was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1928 and became famous for his book illustrations and as a playwright. He began professional life as an architect before swapping a protractor for paintbrush and trained as an artist. He became a prolific ornithological painter and visual watercolour artist also best known for his designs of South African postage stamps, as well as the illustrator for many well-known nature books on the subject of birds and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04rky">mammals</a>. His artworks appear in numerous books and in more than 50 different periodicals. Publications include the First Folio of South African <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015p6">Birds</a> (with Alan Bird, 1959), A Folio of South African Animals (1967), and the illustrations for a prestigious reprint of The Soul of the Ape and The Soul of the White Ant by Eugï¿½ne N. Marais. He also did a mural for the original Jan Smuts Airport in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>. Findlay passed away 28 March 1996.',
