    '1250/1290',
    'An ovaloid-shaped <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m025rs2z">gold</a> foil form which is fragmented. The other sides have a creased border exhibiting a multitude of nail perforations; there are still six gold tacks in situ. The exterior surface is burnished and abraded, while the underside is matt. The gold nails were clearly hammered from the exterior and burnished once in place, as the existing nails have flattened and polished heads. Originating from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of Mapungubwe Hill, grave area dating from CE 1250 to CE 1290.  The archaeological landscape of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a> was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2003. The Mapungubwe Collection is stewarded under the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> where the archaeological collection is on public exhibition for the purposes of research and education.',
