    'Archaeological animal <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> figurine excavated in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of K2, square 2a(i), dating approximately AD 1030 - AD 1220. The figurine has been hand-formed and pinched from a single piece of clay. The figurine consists of two pointed stubs for legs, an udder, tail, torso, head, horns and snout. The torso is rounded and the back is flattened and extends from tail to head in a straight line. The head is characterised by a two horns which extend diagonally upwards from the top of the head. The area between the horns is flattened and the face falls vertically downward into a pointed snout. The udder is positioned between the hind legs and four teats are apparent. The rump is rounded and the tail curves over the rump downwards towards the hind legs. This figurine (N346) forms part of the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of South Africa.',
