    '1926',
    'An etching titled, Woudrichem by the Dutch-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0d060g">Canadian</a> artist Anthonius Philippus (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g120qdsd8">Antoon) Derkzen van Angeren</a> (1879-1961). The work depicts the town <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g121f8xw2">Woudrichem</a> from across the water of the River Waal in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a>. The painting is painted from the small town of Dalem. Short Biography: Antoon Derkzen van Angeren was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a> in the Netherlands in 1878. He first worked at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04825h">Porceleyne Fles</a> ceramic factory as an artist after which he moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06hdk">Rotterdam</a> in 1911 and became a lecturer at the Academy for Fine Arts where he worked until 1943. In 1952, he immigrated to Canada where he passed away in 1961. Derkzen van Angeren is seen as the founder of graphic art in Rotterdam.',
