    'Eric Lubisi',
    '1977',
    'A 1977 woodcut print by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Eric Magamana Lubisi (1946-2020) titled, Basweka Byala (meaning making <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m012mj">alcohol</a> translated from the Zulu titled). The work shows two <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> women brewing beer in traditional ceramic pots. Short Biography: Eric Magamana Lubisi was born in 1946, in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. He grew up with five sisters in Eastwood and was forcibly relocated to Mamelodi when he was twelve during the apartheid regime. Lubisi developed a passion for art and began drawing with charcoal, inspired by his teacher and the renowned South African painter <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0lqfrk5">Gregoire Boonzaier</a>. He pursued his artistic career full-time in 1968 and became known for his symbolic and narrative paintings depicting the struggles of black people under apartheid, often with the themes of hope, justice, and equality. Lubisi held numerous solo and group exhibitions, both locally and internationally, and his artwork is displayed in museums and collections worldwide. He also served as a mentor to young black artists and was recognized for his contributions to the art community. Lubisi passed away in 2020.',
