    'A drawing is titled Commandant Wolmarans, the raffle of clothes (Due to shortages)  by the Dutch / <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0gh6wcz">Frans David Oerder</a> (1867-1944) was drawn on somewhere at the beginning of 1900. During the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0bqtx">South African War</a> (1899-1902) Oerder was paid by the Transvaal Government to paint scenes from the war. He was captured early on and stayed in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> where he painted the everyday life of the British in the capital. Commandant Wolmarans was the Justice of Peace in Potchefstroom before the war, in the drawing the Boers are raffling clothes due to shortages in supplies. Short Biography: Frans Oerder was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06hdk">Rotterdam</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">the Netherlands</a> came to South Africa in 1890. He was mostly known for painting landscapes, still-life and portraits. After the South African War Oerder returned to The Netherlands in 1908 where he settled and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04ztj">married</a> fellow painter Gerda Pitlo in 1910. In 1938 with a second war looming in Europe, Oerder returned to South Africa where he passed away in 1944.',
