    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m068jd">photographic</a> print on Hahnemuhle <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0641k">paper</a> (2018) by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> visual artist, Alet Pretorius titled, In Flames or in Afrikaans, In vlamme. This photographic work captures a powerful moment of enacted displacement. Figures clad in notorious crimson <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09jfs">uniforms</a> lay waste to deconstructed dwellings. The rising heat of a burn pile distorts the picture with a painterly effect. A corrugated zinc panel is hoisted up to a smokey sky before making a slow descent to ash. Pretorius describes the context of the work, ï¿½The Red Ants [are seen] destroying several illegally erected structures on a farm near Soshanguve on 11 September 2018, in Tshwane, South Africa. The farm owners from Limpopo, Dr Motodi Samuel Maserumule and his business partnersï¿½ Diphethe Bopape and Kgosi Letsi Phaahla obtained an eviction order from the High Court. Occupiers allege that they were not given an eviction notice and vowed to rebuild their structures. Short Biography: Alet Pretorius is a visual artist, photojournalist and a part-time lecturer at the School of Arts, University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>. Pretorius''s artwork often portrays the moments between stories about other people and her life events. The photos are neither photojournalism nor fiction. Her artworks often provokes questions but does not try to provide answers. She works as also ​is a freelance photographer, artist and part-time lecturer at Market Photo Workshop and Boston Media House.  She has more than 13 years of photojournalism experience that included a position of Picture Editor at the newspaper, Beeld.  Her photographs have been published in newspapers, magazines, books, and online publications. She has won several awards for her work and has exhibited at various galleries. This work, In Flames (2018) was acquired by the University of Pretoria from the Textured Surfaces exhibition, a staff show of the Department of Visual Arts in 2023 at the University of Pretoria.',
