    'An etching titled, Maas River by the Dutch-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0d060g">Canadian</a> artist Anthonius Philippus (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g120qdsd8">Antoon) Derkzen van Angeren</a> (1879-1961). The Maas or <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0540d">Meuse</a> is a river that runs through the three countries of The Netherlands, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0154j">Belgium</a> and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a>. Short Biography: Antoon Derkzen van Angeren was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">the Netherlands</a> in 1878. He first worked at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04825h">Porceleyne Fles</a> ceramic factory as an artist after which he moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06hdk">Rotterdam</a> in 1911 and became a lecturer at the Academy for Fine Arts where he worked until 1943. In 1952, he immigrated to Canada where he passed away in 1961. Derkzen van Angeren is seen as the founder of graphic art in Rotterdam.',
