    'Philiswa Lila',
    '2019',
    'A beaded installation work from 2019 titled, Simangele by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist, Philiswa Lila (b. 1988). "Simangele", means ï¿½surpriseï¿½ in the Xhosa language. The longitudinal beadwork in fact depicts a pregnancy test: a positive pregnancy test, showing one highlighted stripe, hence a surprise. The artist explores the physical, mental and spiritual spaces of her own experiences by using methods of remembering these as stories. Lila is particularly interested in memory histories and personal identities. As an artist she is influenced by the nuances of language, as she explores individual experiences within the framework of her culture, mainly in the isiXhosa dialect, while also keeping in mind that there is an interconnectedness within the different cultures of South Africa and the many languages of the country. The notion of language in her work is explored within the meaning and experiences of individualism, especially concerning the physical and emotional senses that is related to humans and animals. Lila works across disciplines such a painting, drawing, bead <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a>, performance and writing. In her practice, she explores different mediums to create artworks that reflect elements of animal skin (such as sheep, goat and cow), beading, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wood</a>, Paper and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07z4p">video</a>. Short biography: Philiswa Lila was born in 1988 in South Africa. She is a multimedia artist and scholar based in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, South Africa. She has a B-Tech degree in Fine and Applied Art (Tshwane University of Technology), an Honours degree in Curatorship (University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a>) and a Masters in Art History (Rhodes University). In 2019, Philiswa completed a residency at the Citï¿½ Internationale des Arts in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0f8l9c">France</a> after winning the prestigious Absa L''Atelier Gerard Sekoto Award in 2018. In 2020, the Absa Gallery hosted her well-received debut solo exhibition, titled Skin, Bone, Fire: The First Album. This exhibition then toured to various venues in South Africa in association with the Alliance Francaise. The famous South Africa doyenne and Ndebele artist Dr <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0j42hzh">Esther Mahlangu</a> selected Philiswa as her ï¿½artist to watchï¿½ for the 2019 SEED auction.',
