    'Isaac Seoka',
    '2011',
    'A large fountain feature titled, Swimming Against the Current depicts 34 <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ch_cf">fish</a> swimming upstream by the South African sculptor, Isaac (Sakkie) Seoka (b.1967). This work was part of a commission of works created for the new main entrance at University Road to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>ï¿½s Hatfield campus in 2011. Seoka a Venda born artist began carving the work in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wood</a> as another <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> sculptor, Guy du Toit (b.1958) assisted him to make the wax works for casting. The work was created with the idea of the fish as a symbol of knowledge, swimming upstream. According to Seoka, the university is an institution of knowledge where students must swim against the current of today in order to achieve a better future. Seoka also works as the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> studio technician for the School of Arts at the University of Pretoria.',
