(
    'Bertha Everard',
    '1926',
    'Delville Wood, Landscape with Crater was painted by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Bertha Everard (1873-1965). Delville Wood was a battle fought between the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> and the German forces during the First <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">World War (1914-1918</a>). The Battle of Delville Wood continued from 14 July to 3 September, was an engagement in the 1916 <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0gjw_">Battle of the Somme</a>. The Wood was captured by the South African Infantry Brigade on 15 July 1916 and was held until 19 July at a very high cost on casualties as the wood formed a salient and was bombed by the German forces from three sided. The thick wood was nearly demolished by the bombings and in 1926, 10 years later, when Everard visited the site it was still only crates and stumps. Everard donated the painting after the Everard Group exhibited at the MacFadyen Memorial Hall on 19 October 1935. Short biography: Bertha (King) Everard was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a>, South Africa in 1873. Everard was initially trained as a pianist in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0fhp9">Vienna</a> but later studied painting between 1893 and 1899 at various schools in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02jx1">England</a>, including the Slade and Westminster art schools in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> and the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m013p1n">St Ives</a> School of Landscape in Cornwall. In 1902, Everard began teaching at the Staats Model School in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> but after marrying Charles Everard in 1903, she moved with him to Bonnefoi, a small trading post on the Eastern Transvaal escarpment near Carolina. In 1910, Everard won a gold <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m020yd1">medal</a> at the South African National Union art exhibition in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a>, organised by Florence Phillips, with a landscape painting in oils. Everard accompanied her two daughters Ruth and Rosamund to be educated in Europe in the 1920s and lived between England and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a>, exhibiting at the Royal Academy in London in 1923 and on the Paris Salon in 1924 and 1926. Everard returned to South Africa to live on the farm in 1926, painting mostly landscapes and exclusively in oils. Her work was shown at the Empire Exhibition in Johannesburg in 1936 and, in 1967, the Pretoria Art Museum held a prestige retrospective exhibition of the work of ï¿½The Everard Groupï¿½ ­ï¿½ Bertha Everard, her daughters Ruth and Rosamund, and her sister Edith King.',
