    'Margaret Gradwell',
    '2010',
    'Portrait of Dr NM Hoogenhout by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist, Margaret Slabbert (b.1956). Dr Nicolaas Marais Hoogenhout (1876-1932) was the second Principal of the University of Pretoria and his tenure stretched between 1925 and 1927. The official commission of key portraits and hence, the foundation of what is referred to as the portrait collection within the University of Pretoria, began on 9 September 1974. Prof AN Pelzer (Vice-Rector) suggested that the university commence a commission of key portraits of former Chancellors, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01mzpv">Chairs</a> of the Council and Principals or Rectors. Short Biography: Margaret Slabbert was born in 1956 in Pretoria using mainly her maiden surname, Margaret Gradwell as a South African artist. She studied at University of Pretoria where she also became a lecturer in 1980 and in 1999 she became an associate Professor. Gradwellï¿½s work appears  in private, corporate, public and diplomatic collections, amongst others: Mayorï¿½s Office of the City of Tshwane, University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, Pretoria Art Museum, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c59j">Pietersburg</a> Art Gallery, HSRC, Lifegro, Saambou, Klerksdorp Municipality, Department of Education and Training, Pretoria, Technikon, Pretoria, UNISA School for Business Leadership, SASOL, Telkom, ABSA Towers (commissioned work), and National Museum for Women in the Arts, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0rh6k">Washington DC</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09c7w0">USA</a>. Her work depicts dynamic dualistic landscapes and open still life.',
