    'Juliet Armstrong',
    '2001',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramic</a> artwork titled Isibodiya for a Friend by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> ceramicist Juliet Armstrong (1950-2012). A Isibodiya is a Zulu apron used during the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m081hv">wedding ceremony</a> , it is normally made of the skin of a young buck. In this case it was carefully constructed from thin <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m016f4d">porcelain</a> layers. Short Biography: Juliet Yvonne Armstrong was born in 1950 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a> in KwaZulu Natal. She studied from 1968-1972 at the University of Natal where she later became a lecturer and professor herself. Armstrong  became known as one of the most remarkable ceramicist and ceramic educators in the country. She passed away in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01_vrh">Pietermaritzburg</a> in 2012.',
