    'A Napoleonic War Dutch commemorative wall plate dated 1933 designed by the Dutch ceramicist, WC Brouwer (1877-1933). This plate celebrates 100 years (1813-1913) of Independence of The Netherlands after the Napoleonic Wars. The turquoise glaze on <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m017jcd">terracotta</a> depicts a new dawn for The Netherlands with the inscription in Dutch, ï¿½De Vryheid <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06rrc">Shoes</a>ï¿½  translated as "Of the Hat of Freedom", depicting a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02dl1y">hat</a> surmounted on a central pole. The back of the plate is partially glazed and has the Brouwer stamp and numerals stamped in clay. The design was executed by Dutch <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">ceramic</a> artist, Willem Coenraad Brouwer (1877-1933) in his private studio which started in 1906 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0wbfy">Leiderdorp</a>, The Netherlands. This plate together with most of the commemorative Dutch war ware was donated by Louise van Gybland Oosterhoff in 1937 to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> as the first of a three part donation of items and documents on Dutch history.',
