    'A carved <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wooden</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> dated 1980 by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist, Julius Napaqu Mfethe (1956-2008) titled Baboon Trap. The work depicts a baboon that is walking up to a pumpkin. Baboons love to eat pumpkin pips. Farmers in an attempt to capture a baboon, especially since the trops damages crops, a pumpkin is cut open with a hole big enough for the baboon to put his hand in when it is open, but too small to take it out when it is in a fist position. The baboon does not know that he can open his fist and take it out and therefore gets trapped. Short Biography: Julius Napaqu Mfethe (1956-2008) was born in Port St Johnï¿½s in the Eastern Cape and is a self-taught artist. His works are realistic, presenting actual domestic chores and often animal subjects. All his works are carved from wood collected from the bush surrounding his homestead. Mfethe passed away in his home town in 2008.',
