    'Mmangaliso Nzuza',
    '2022',
    'A painting titled, Everyday by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Mmangaliso Nzuza (b. 1998). The work reflects the artist''s idea to work through his own artistic process and then depicts his experience of art in the form of fictional characters. In this case, everyday life which looks at his experience and struggles each day as an emerging young black artist amplified and influenced by the pandemic and Black Lives Matter Movement. Short Biography: Mmangaliso (or Mmango) Nzuza was born in Empangeni near <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjvv">Durban</a> in Kwa-Zulu Natal. Inspired by a teacher in preparatory school, Mmango pursued art through high school, delving into different mediums but primarily sticking to pencil and charcoal. He is best known for his figurative oil paintings that express his battle with social anxiety. Nzuza completed a MA(Hons) Government, Policy and Society at the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02m77">Edinburgh</a> in 2022, after which he continued to resume his practice as a self-taught artist. Known for his cubism-influenced and rich texture-filled artworks, which tell a story that resonates with battling loneliness and navigating the self. His works are inspired by his own personal history and popular culture. The idea of stagnation and mental health development is a recurring theme in his work and for him, the forming of his figures is a means of uncovering an individualï¿½s character. This is a core focus of his practice and his oil paintings flourished mainly since the 2020 <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g11fr15t15h">Covid-19 pandemic</a>. Growing up in a rigid and conservative environment, Nzuza used art as an outlet to portray the complexity and optimism of his experience, an extension of his past, the present, and the future. Art serves as a personal quest in an attempt to materialize his experience and for others, on their displacement through the use of colour symbolism, often using neutral colours. Using a distinctive technique that involves creating disjointed lines and colours, exploring the unexpected harmony in the imbalance and imperfections. In turn, creating unique compositions that simultaneously reflect his life. Nzuza continues to work as a self-taught visual artist and lives in Durban.',
