    'Erich Mayer',
    '1940',
    'A small <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m018ktp">watercolour</a> of San rock art by the German born,  South African artist, Ernst Karl (Erich) Mayer (1876-1960). Mayer travelled South Africa extensively  and used his popular representative style to capture the lives of ordinary rural <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africans</a> and their environments on canvas. The Blaauwberg is an iconic blue haze mountain range adjacent to the Soutpansberg <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09d_r">mountains</a> that stretches nearly 900 km in the Limpopo Province of South Africa and apparently this watercolour depicts some of the San paintings he came across in his travels. Short Biography: Ernst Karl (Erich) Mayer was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0qb1z">Karlsruhe</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a> in 1876.  In 1894 he was awarded a bursary to study architecture at Charlottenburg Technische Hochschule in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0156q">Berlin</a>, but had to discontinue his studies due to ill health in 1896 but was officially trained as an architect in Berlin. Mayer came to South Africa in 1898 to work as a land surveyor in the Free State and later imigrated north to the Transvaal. Just over a year after coming to the Transvaal, the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0bqtx">South African War</a> (1899-1902) broke out and he was called to arms to join on the Boer side, he was captured and sent to St. Helena Island as a Prisoner of War.  After the war, he commenced his career as an artist, mostly painting small watercolour works. He settled in Pretoria and would often go out into the countryside on painting trips with his friend J F <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m043cgm">Pierneef</a>, who also taught Mayer the art of woodcut printing.  In the First <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">World War (1914-1918</a>), as well as the Second World War (1939-1945) Mayer was intered yet again in prisoner of war camps due to his German descent. Erich Mayer died in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">pretoria</a> in 1960.',
