    'Viola Greyling',
    '2018',
    'A set of seven painted earthenware <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02s195">vases</a> titled, Back and Forth (2018) by the South African ceramicist Viola Greyling. The artist has commented about this work as, "Many <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> citizens can relate to the sense of displacement since most of the current generation do not know how to position themselves within this ï¿½newï¿½ South Africa. In my artworks I use water and clouds as a metaphor to portray the feeling of anxiety and dislocation." In the series of vases ï¿½Back and forthï¿½  she utilised handmade earthenware vases covered in multiple pictorial narratives to underscore the fact that one creates and fashions our own "person hoods". The various fragments of the tangled identity are formed through layers of brushstrokes that create disjointed, multidimensional collage images. While, Greyling uses personal family photographs, none of the people are recognizable, which enables the viewer to connect with the artworks. Yet, even though the public is invited to participate in the artwork, these series of images and objects remain a deeply personal reflection and cathartic exploration of the artists own complicated and confused sense of being South African.',
