    'Archaeological human clay figurine fragment excavated from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of Mapungubwe Hill, block 5, section 1, dating approximately AD 1220 - AD 1290.The figurine is a female torso consisting of hips, upper thighs, buttocks and navel. The slim, cylindrical waist which is flattened expands into rounded hips. The figurine is characterised by a protruding navel with incised decoration surrounding it. A set of five incised  lines radiate to the left and right of the navel, a short double line extends downwards and two bands of horizontally drawn short scratches that extend vertically upwards from the navel. On the sides and back of the buttocks, intricate decoration is evident; diagonal lines stretch over the buttocks area in a band- like formation, the lines are split by a single incision. The upper part of the band is cut by three sets of short, vertical lines. Below the navel is a small perforation.This figurine (N303) forms part of the Mapungubwe National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of South Africa.',
