    'David Canty',
    '1934',
    'A <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m018ktp">watercolour painting</a> by the English <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist David Canty (1870-1936) titled in Afrikaans, "Naboom" popularly known as the candelabra tree (Euphorbia ingens). Works by Canty, like this watercolour, were painted to document the landscape, rather than the work intended as an artwork. Many other South African landscape artists such as Johannes Cornelius Poortemans, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m08brqz">Thomas Baines</a>, Abraham de Smidt and William John Burchell are well-known for depicting scenes of the Cape. However, Canty''s contributions are lesser known. Short Biography: David Canty was born 28 February in 1870 in Mitchelstown in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0clz7">Cork, Ireland</a>. He studied at the Art School in Cork and later moved to South Africa after he was offered employment at the De Beers Diamond Company in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01tjpx">Kimberley</a>. After 1903, he moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0c59j">Pietersburg</a> and worked as an artist until about 1913, producing more than 105 works of art. Canty is known for his Transvaal English landscapes and later mastered his subject matter like other South African landscape painters such as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m043cgm">Hendrik Pierneef</a>, Hugo Naude and Erich Mayer and he was one of the first and most important Transvaal painters with <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0gh6wcz">Frans Oerder</a>. Canty retired to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1926, where he passed away in 1936.',
