    'A painting titled Mont-aux-Sources by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Willem Hermanus Coetzer (1900-1983). <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09d_r">Mont</a>-aux-Sources is one of the highest points of the Drakensberg range located between the province of KwaZulu Natal in South Africa and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04hvw">Lesotho</a>. One of the largest rivers in KwaZulu Natal originates in the peak, namely the Tugela River. Short Biography: Willem Hermanus Coetzer was born in Tarkastad in 1900, He studied in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> at various institutions from 1928 to 1935. He became a renowned Afrikaner Nationalist painter, painting mostly scenes from the Great Trek, a historical movement of White pioneers, called the Voortrekkers who moved from todays Cape Province to Natal (1836-1838). The pinnacle of his work was the design of 15 historical tapestries for the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02cnny">Voortrekker Monument</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>.',
