    'An archaeological animal <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0975t">clay</a> figurine from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Iron Age <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0h61">archaeological</a> site of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07h3lt">Mapungubwe</a> Hill, from the base known as the southern Terrace, from excavation Square K8, layer 7, dating approximately from AD 1220 - AD 1290.The figurine has been hand-formed and pinched from a single piece of clay. The figurine most probably depicts a sheep (ovis aries), comprising of four pointed stubs for legs, torso, neck, head and snout. The torso is well rounded and extends into an elongated neck and flattened head with a pointed snout. The dewlap extends downwards from snout to just above the front legs The legs are mere extensions of the torso and the animal stands on the pointed ends of the legs. The back side is flattened and no distinguishable tail is apparent due to material loss. This figurine (N318) forms part of the Mapungubwe National Heritage Collection- specifically declared as a heritage object of South Africa.',
