    'Mickey Korzennik',
    '2009',
    'A bronze sculpture titled, Eddie Ladan by the South African artist Jean Doyle (b.1930). Jean Doyle created this satirical work of Eduard Louis "Eddie" Ladan (1918-1992) an artist and art critic. Ladan had very harsh critique of Doyles work after which she crated the work as a bit of payback. Short Biography: Jean Doyle was born in Wynberg in the Western Cape in 1930 and is a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> Postwar and Contemporary sculptor . She studied at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a> Training College between 1961 and 1963. Doyle mostly specializes in the veneration of the fuller female figure in her bronze <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculptures</a> and her series of art deco and other female portaits of fuller women figures is her signature style. Doyle is an internationally-recognised sculptor from South Africa whose trademark of the fuller female-figure offers interesting social critiques and is a tool on social commentary of women in society. Her bronze works often reflect the Spirit of Women bronze sculptures, African images of women, some miniature bronzes and lifesize bronze sculptures. Jean has won international commissions which include the famous dog named, Just Nuisance in Simons Town, South Africa, two diamond miners for Diamonds South Africa (Pty) Ltd; and Kifangondo, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0j4b">Angola''s</a> National Monument which depicts National Freedom. Kifangondo is considered to be one of the largest artworks on the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">African</a> Continent - it weighs just under 8 tonnes, stands 9 metres high and took just under a year to complete.',
