    'Livingstone Gocini',
    '1977',
    'A woodcut print by the South African artist, Mpathi Livingstone Patekile Gocini (b.1957) titled, An Orphan. Gocini''s works are rather political and  is a reminder of the children who suffered under the brutal <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> apartheid regime. Short Biography: Mpathi Livingstone Patekile Gocini as born in 1957 in King Williams Town, today''s <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ks3s">Qonce</a> in the Eastern Cape Province of South Africa. He began to create artwork whilst still in primary school. Later in 1976, the black consciousness leader <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m070dl">Steve Biko</a> (1946-1977) arranged for a bursary for Gocini to study at the Rorke''s Drift Art School. In 1979, Gocini enrolled in the Michaelis School of Fine Arts in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01yj2">Cape Town</a>, but due to his strong political activism  he went to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04hvw">Lesotho</a> in the same year. In Lesotho, Gocini began an art weaving project which led in to Cape Town where he has taught weaving since 1933.',
