    'Antoon Derkzen van Angeren',
    '1932',
    'An etching, titled Large Tower, Zaltbommel by the Dutch-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0d060g">Canadian</a> born artist Anthonius Philippus (<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g120qdsd8">Antoon) Derkzen van Angeren</a> (1879-1961). The work depicts the River Waal in the town <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0vkjx">Zaltbommel</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a>. In the background, is the tower of a brick factory.  Short Biography: Antoon Derkzen van Angeren was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a> in the Netherlands in 1878. He first worked at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04825h">Porceleyne Fles</a> ceramic factory as an artist after which he moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06hdk">Rotterdam</a> in 1911 and became a lecturer at the Academy for Fine Arts where he worked until 1943. In 1952, he immigrated to Canada where he passed away in 1961. Derkzen van Angeren is seen as the founder of graphic art in Rotterdam.',
