    'Kerry Goodwin',
    '2014',
    'A small delicate <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m016f4d">porcelain</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02s195">vase</a>  by designer, Kerry Goodwin for the Moorcroft factory as a commemoration to mark the centenary of the outbreak of the First <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0cm2xh">World War (1914-1918</a>).  The vase has distinctive images which emerge directly from the mud-filled  war trenches, the brutal weapons of destruction and scatters them across a barren, scarred landscape. But watching over the derelict battlefield from the clouds above are the silhouettes of the soldiers who paid the ultimate price for their country. Even so, they live on among the destruction  with the metal remains of a wrecked tank illustrated among bright red poppies, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03vt0">insects</a> and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m015p6">birds</a> that came back to the landscape once the silence returned. The poppy, is the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">United Kingdom''s</a> national symbol of remembrance and a Moorcroft speciality for more than 100 years and was specially chosen to depict this series in their Collection of Remembrance.The name of the Moorcroft design, "Lest we Forget" originates from a 1897 poem by Rudyard Kipling who, in the same year that William Moorcroft first started designing in 1897 titled, ''Recessionalï¿½: ï¿½The tumult and the shouting dies; The Captains and the Kings depart: Still stands Thine ancient sacrifice, A humble and a contrite heart. Lord God of Hosts, be with us yet, Lest we forgetï¿½lest we forget!"',
