    'Seymour Kirkup',
    '1841',
    'A tracing of the Portrait of Dante by Seymour Kirkup (1788-1880) from the painting originally done by Giotto. In the last 150 years many articles and books have been written on the artwork representing Dante Alighieri (1265-1321) by the famous early Renaissance painter, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0kp91">Giotto di Bondone</a> (1266-1337). Many things have been said about the painting and there is much doubt whether it was actually executed by Giotto. The portrait of Dante was painted between 1290 and 1336. The painting, part of a fresco, was executed in the chapel of the Palace of the Podestï¿½ in Florence. During the sixteenth or seventeenth century the once elaborate paintings in the chapel were covered with whitewash and the chapel was converted into a storeroom for the prison that the palace became. Here the Dante portrait by the hand of Giotto was to lay hidden for many years. The rediscovery and restoration of the Dante portrait by Giotto tells a very interesting story. In the early to middle nineteenth century, three scholars, devoted to the works of Dante, started a search for the long lost painting which had been mentioned and described by <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01596r">Lorenzo Ghiberti</a> (1379-1455) in his Commentarii. The three 19th century scholars were Richard Henry Wilde (1789-1847), an American, Seymour Stocker Kirkup (1788-1880), an Englishman and an Italian, Giovanni Aubrey Bezzi. After much deliberation with the Italian Government, a Florentine painter, Antonio Marini (1788-1861), was entrusted with the removal of the whitewash from the chapel walls. After a couple of months, the long lost portrait of Dante was rediscovered on 21 July 1840. Kirkup in a letter to the Spectator (London) on 11 May 1850 explained that for a long time he had been prevented from making a drawing of the portrait in the chapel. Eventually in 1841 he obtained permission to be shut up in the prison for a morning, and in this time he made a drawing and a tracing of the work. A facsimile of Kirkupï¿½s drawing was passed on to George James Warren Lord Vernon the 5th (1803-1866) and it was published by the Arundel Society in 1859 as a chromo-lithograph. Kirkup gave his tracing, this <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m063w2">pencil</a> sketch, to his friend Gabriel Rossetti, who in turn gave it to his son, the famous English Pre-Raphaelite painter, Dante Gabriel Rossetti (1828-1882). This tracing was sold in 1882 after <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03xpqgs">Dante Gabriel Rossetti</a>ï¿½s death. In 1940 the work was sold at auction in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> and bought by the Dutch art collector Jacob van Tilburg (1888-1980). In 1976 he bequeathed the largest part of his collection to the University of Pretoria.',
