    'A small <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01brf">bronze</a> head by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Martin Qgibinsizi Tose (1958-2004). Short Biography: Martin Tose was born in 1958 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04_jp6">Germiston</a>, Johannesburg, South Africa. He established himself as a sculptor, graphic artist and a painter during his late teens. Tose attended part-time art classes at the Open School in Braamfontein, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> under the guidance of Nathaniel Mokgosi between 1975 and 1977. The Open School was opened in 1974 to equip high school learners with foundational skills in fine art and music. He spent the next three years until 1980 at Katlehong Art Centre, studying under Thato Mamabolo whom trained at Ndaleni Teacherï¿½s Training College in KwaZulu Natal. From 1984, he taught at the same art centre as was considered a post war and contemporary artist. Since 1978 he participated in various group exhibitions until his premature death at the young age of 46. Although his life was cut short by kidney complications, Toseï¿½s work forms part of many collections of major banks, universities and national galleries in the country. He died in 2004 in the Ekurhuleni township of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05rlh1">Katlehong</a>, southeast of Johannesburg.',
