    'A drawing by the German, Namibia artist Fritz Krampe (1913-1966). The Bulls in the drawing is young Afrikaner Bulls, a cross specie of cattle found in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa</a>. Short Biography: Fritz Krampe was born in 1913 in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0156q">Berlin</a> <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a>. He studied in 1933 at the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02h6_6p">Munich</a> Fine Arts Academy and from 1935 to 1939 at the Prussian Academy of Art as a master student. After being captured in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m02k54">Egypt</a> as a POW in 1941 he was held in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0chghy">Australia</a> and moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0ftq7">Windhoek</a> in South West Africa, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05bmq">Namibia</a> today, in 1950. He traveled the world extensively and visited Siberia, India and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05sb1">Pakistan</a>. During one of these trips in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rk0">India</a> he was killed by an elephant, being gored by its trust in the Anaikatti Jungle, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m012n8khs">Ootacamund</a> in 1966.',
