(
    'Erich Mayer',
    '1909',
    'This work titled, Donga or on the Spruit is by the German-born, South African artist Ernst Karl (Erich) Mayer (1876-1960). Mayer lived in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> and between 1910 and 1913, the iconic construction of the Union Buildings, as the official seat of the new South African government at the time was one of the main events in his capital city. This small painting was completed in 1909 and predates the Union, but is painted from the view of a drift in the Apies River in Pretoria that is located on the corner of President and Rissik streets. On the left on the horizon is Meintjieskop, where the Union Buildings construction would soon commence. Short Biography: Ernst Karl (Erich) Mayer (1876-1960) was born in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0qb1z">Karlsruhe</a> in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0345h">Germany</a> in 1876, he immigrated to South Africa to the Transvaal in 1898. Soon after the Transvaal  <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0bqtx">South African War</a> (1899-1902) broke out,  and he joined the call to arms on the Boer side. He was captured and sent to St. Helena Island as a Prisoner of War. Erich Mayer trained as an architect in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0156q">Berlin</a>, Germany, and came to South Africa in 1898 to work as a land surveyor in the Free State. He joined the Boer commandos during the South African War (1899ï¿½1902) and spent time as a Prisoner of War on St Helena. The University of Pretoria has several works by Mayer who used his popular representative style to capture the lives of ordinary rural <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africans</a> and their environments on Canvas.Mayer decided to further his studies and moved to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m031y2">Florence</a>, <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03rjj">Italy</a> for a year in 1935, studying under Chini and Annigonni. Upon his return he exhibited around the country. Erich Mayer was awarded a <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m020yd1">Medal</a> of Honour for painting by the South African Academy  in 1943. Mayer''s works are highly sought after as his paintings depict a fairly comprehensive record of rural South African life and scenery during the first half of the 20th Century.  Mayer''s works are iconic of South African art as throughout his artistic career he adopted such an intense South African character. Erich Mayer died in Pretoria in 1960.',
