(
    'Emilia Muhinda',
    '2003',
    'A silkscreen  titled, Tree of life by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0j4b">Angolan</a>-<a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> artist Emilia Kuvangu Mahinda (b.1950). This work pays homage to the San communities who occupy the desert regions of southern <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dg3n1">Africa</a> and where <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07j7r">trees</a> are considered as spiritual and seen as life giving forces. Trees also represent a source of food, heat and water. Short Biography: Emelia Kuvangu Muhinda was born in Angola during the 1950s. Her mother played a vital role in her upbringing, imparting traditional San knowledge and survival skills that included navigating the veld and identifying indigenous medicinal herbs. Mahinda carries with he as an artist, the knowledge of diverse San folktales, with her grandmother also being a significant source of such culturally-rich stories. In the early 1970s, Mahinda  joined the !Xun exodus from Angola to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05bmq">Namibia</a> and settled in the Omega Military Camp for refugees. For over two decades, she resided there until the traditional communities were eventually forced to relocate to South Africa in 1991.',
