    'This vertical porcelain beaker-shaped ceramic tea light or candle holder is designed by the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South African</a> ceramicist, Carolyn Heydenrych. Inspired and reminiscent of the archaeological K2 low-fired earthenware beakers, this particular holder is folded at the thin walled seam and incised with fine Mapungubwe type, chevron decoration. Heydenrych uses the beautiful medium of porcelain with its fine texture and creamy neutral colour and is drawn to porcelain for its delicacy as well as its similarity to Paper. The artist''s signature works are with clay and black pen, as Paper architectural drawings. Most of her style strives to achieve extremely thin sides with windows even thinner to express the light shining through like architectural elevational walls. Heydenrych has contributed several articles to the National <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01x5q">Ceramics</a> magazine and has works in the Pretoria Art Museum and University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> collections. In 2010, she won the Glazecor Premier Award at the Ceramics SA Ultra-Furn Regional exhibition in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> for her <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m016f4d">porcelain</a> tea set.',
