    'The drum major mace of the 94th Regiment of Foot from the <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m07ssc">British</a> Army line infantry regiment. The staff is  fashioned from base <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04t7l">metal</a> and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m083vt">wood</a>. The staff was taken from the regiment in 1880 after their defeat against General Piet Joubert (1831-1900) at the Battle of Bronkhorstspruit, east of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a>, in the First Freedom War (1880-1881) between the South African Republic and the British, also called the First Boer War. The Battle of Bronkhorstspruit was the first major engagement of the First Boer War. It took place by the Bronkhorstspruit river, near the town of Bronkhorstspruit in the former Transvaal, on 20 December 1880. The staff was was donated to the University of Pretoria by a private collector of the family of one of the boer soldiers that had  fought in the Battle. The British regiment''s commanding officer was Lieutenant Colonel Philip Robert <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m049h3l">Anstruther</a> and they surrendered to the boers only 15 minutes after battle and after heavy casualties and most probably relinquished the staff.',
