    'Christo Coetzee',
    '1987',
    'Paris Remake, 1956. Art Autre Gallery Stadler is a Mixed Media avant-garde <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06msq">sculpture</a> by the South African artist Christo Coetzee (1929-2000). In 1955 Christo Coetzee became part of the famous Stadler Sable avant-garde art group in Paris. The Stadler Galleries owner Rodolphe Stadler saw the merit in avant-garde art and exhibited several artists in this genre. In 1956 Coetzee created a painted typewriter simply titled ï¿½Art Autreï¿½, named so after Michael Tapiï¿½''s (1909-1987) publication in 1952, and exhibited it at his solo exhibition at the Stadler Gallery in 1961. In 1987 when exhibiting at the Randse Afrikaanse Universiteit (Rand Afrikaans University), Coetzee could not find the typewriter and recreated it for the exhibition as he believed it to be one of his most important works. Other important Pop artists like <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01sj_s">Robert Rauschenberg</a> (1925-2008) and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m01zgr1">Claes Oldenburg</a> (1929-2002) created similar works in the early 1960s. The object was donated to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> by the artist in 1991 at a retrospective exhibition held at the Intersaal on the campus, along with nearly 50 other works and subsequently his entire estate. Short biography: The Johannesburg born artist, Christo Coetzee pursued his art studies at the Slade School of Art in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m04jpl">London</a> as a complementary tuition exercise to his fine art degree qualification acquired from the University of the Witwatersrand in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0g284">Johannesburg</a> South Africa. Most of Coetzee''s works are mainly colourful, stylized figurative images and still lifes. After completing his studies he moved to Europe on a Government Travelling Scholarship and become part of the Stadler Stable in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m05qtj">Paris</a> before moving to Finestrat in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m06mkj">Spain</a>. Later, Coetzee went to <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m03_3d">Japan</a> where he was invited to join the Gutai Group, the first radical Art Group in post-war Japan. It was in Japan that Coetzee developed his recognisable art style that ultimately classified him as <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0hzlz">South Africa''s</a> leading and prominent avant-garde artists. Coetzee received international recognition for his contribution to the avant-garde art movements known as Art Informel, Assemblage and Neo-Baroque in Paris, Spain and Japan during the 1950s and 1960s, an art style he perfected. He passed away at the age of 71 in 2000 in Tulbagh in the Cape and bequeathed his entire home and collection to the University of Pretoria.',
