    'Plateelbakkerij Delft',
    '1913',
    'A Napoleonic War Dutch Plateelbakkerij Delft or <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m064rk">Pottery</a> Bakery Delft commemorative plate is one of a set consisting of 14 plates. The pottery that made these, although they had <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m029t1">Delft</a>, a town in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m059j2">The Netherlands</a> in their name was made in <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0k3p">Amsterdam</a>. Decorated in blue and red the plate commemorates the writing of the Dutch constitution and the creators of the Dutch Monarchy. In the center is a crown and the name of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m098q8">Willem I</a> who was crowned as King of the Netherlands on 30 November 1813. On the rim the names of several key figures in this process. <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m09f6nc">Gijsbert Karel van Hogendorp</a> (1762-1834) the chairman of the commission; Anton Reinhard Falck (1777-1843); <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m0dyz0w">Leopold Karel, Count of Limburg Stirum</a> (1758-1840); Cornelis Anthony Fannius Scholten (1767-1832); Frans Adam van der Duyn van Maasdam (1771-1848); and <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/g122qx_5d">Joan Melchior Kemper</a> (1776-1824).The plate was donated by Louise van Gybland Oosterhoff to the University of <a href="https://artsandculture.google.com/entity/m067z4">Pretoria</a> in 1937.',
